Commentary.Commentary: 47 overs left in the day but around 25 minutes to go to Tea. South Africa will hope to ride this period off and get a substantial score by the end of the day, perhaps even going past the Lankan total. The players are back out in the middle. Dean Elgar and Aiden Markram are the openers for South Africa. Vishwa Fernando to start. Elgar to face. 'Play!' says Marais Erasmus.

Perfect outing for the Proteas. Especially, when they did not know what to do on the deck. JP Duminy mentioned that the first hour is very crucial, during his pitch report, but ironically, it is after that first hour when things started to happen. The hosts took a while to get used to the lengths and lines to be bowled but once they found their mark, they were very consistent. Wiaan Mulder started the procession, breaking the 52-wicket stand for the second wicket, getting rid of Kusal Perera. In fact, that passage, where he took 3 wickets in 11 balls, lifted the entire team. Anrich Nortje then found his inner self and polished the rest of the batting order. Or nearly the rest. He took 6, while Sipamla got one in between.

Tough pill to swallow. You choose to bat, get to 72/1, seem well on top of the opposition and then suddenly, the table is overturned. After losing Dimuth Karunaratne early, Kusal Perera played the Adam Gilchrist/Matthew Haydenesque type of cricket, attacking the bowling and getting them off their plans. For a good part of an hour, he seemed successful. He got to his half century quickly but then, eventually, got out too. A look at that shot and you will criticize him, but that is the way attacking batsmen play - live by the sword and die by it too. What happened after that was not quite thought of, with the middle order feebly getting out. A bit of resistance from the lower middle order pushed the score past 150 but that is not a competitive score by any stretch of imagination.

243 legal balls. That is all it has taken for the South African pace attack to dismantle the Lankans. Not even an entire innings of an ODI. Just 4 bowlers used, two of those sharing 90 percent of those wickets and Anrich Nortje picking up a 6-fer. They have decimated the Lankan batting order, which simply had no idea on how to play on a bouncy track.

OUT! BOWLED! Lock, stock and barrell. Not difficult to think of. Asitha was telegraphing his basic intentions, wanting to stay away from the ball, so that the body does not get hit and Nortje does the perfect two-card trick. Two short balls, sets him up, makes him think that another short one is coming but then, fires it on the stumps. Fernando backs away, is too late to adjust and misses it comprehensively. The stumps are shattered. SRI LANKA BOWLED OUT FOR 157!
Another tail-ender slog. A short ball, outside off, Asitha backs away, slogs wildly, is nowhere even remotely close to the ball.
FOUR! Off the edge and over the slips. A typical tail-ender shot. A length ball, outside off, Fernando slashes hard but gets a thick outside edge, well over the slips, to the third man fence.
A bouncer, right at the head, ducked under in a hurry.
Very full, around off, pushed towards mid on.
Good bowling. On a length, outside off, Fernando feels for it but then misses.
Outside off, on a good length, left alone.
Full and outside off, driven back past the bowler, for a couple, before extra cover can get to it.
A length ball, Vishwa targets Cape Town with his slog, connects with thin air.
Another short ball, outside off, ducked under.
Outside off, on a length, angling away, swayed away from.
A short ball, but way down the leg side, comfortably let through.
Debutant Asitha Fernando is the last man in.

OUT! CAUGHT BY THE KEEPER! There it is! 5 wickets for Anrich Nortje! Second 5-fer in Tests for the fast and nasty bowler. A short ball, from around the wicket, pitched around leg, angling away, Chameera looks to pull but the ball rises steeply, takes the top edge and goes through to Quinton de Kock. Sri Lanka are 9 down.
JUST SHORT! A short ball, at the body, Chameera gets across, looks to tuck it to the leg side but ends up fending it. Short leg dives forward for the catch but is not able to get there.

Oh hello. Time for some shots. A length ball, outside off, Chameera backs away and swings hard. He gets more height than distance as the ball goes really high in the air. But he manages to clear mid off running back. 2 runs taken to bring up the 150 FOR SRI LANKA.
Anrich Nortje returns. 13-1-50-4 so far.
Full and outside off, VF lunges and then shoulders arms.
Full and outside off, a touch wide, Vishwa goes chasing and misses.
On a length, outside off, pushed to the off side.
Full and outside off, left alone.

EDGED, DROPPED! Temba Bavuma, of all the people! Unbelievable. Full and outside off, Fernando hangs his bat out, tamely. The ball comes in, hits the edge and flies straight to Temba Bavuma. He comes forward, seems to take it but then, the ball falls out. This is what happens when you don't have regular slip fielders.
Vishwa Fernando walks in now.

OUT! CAUGHT BY THE KEEPER! Another on-field decision stands. Pretty much similar to the Shanaka dismissal. A length ball, outside off, angling away, Hasaranga pushes at it but misses. There is a noise though, as the ball passes through. Sipamla appeals, the umpire raises his finger but Hasaranga signals the 'T'. Replays too, indicate some noise while UltraEdge shows a spike. End of a nice cameo.
Gone? Yes! Or no? Seems like Hasaranga has edged it, as per the sound but he takes the review. UltraEdge comes and Hasaranga goes. Another review taken, just for the sake of it.

DRINKS BREAK. Well, not bad. Sri Lanka have managed to hang on till the first hour after the Lunch break. Did not seem that way when play resumed. Hasaranga has played some counter-attacking shots while Chameera has given him good company. This can happen, with the Proteas perhaps trying a bit too hard. Need to focus and gather all their thoughts back.

Back of a length around off, Chameera tucks this towards deep square aand collects a brace. Keshav Maharaj chases the ball and throws it back towards the keeper. However, it is a wide one and de Kock has to stretch to his left to collect. Had the throw been accurate, Chameera was a goner here.
Length ball around off, blocked on the back foot.
Length ball around off, Chameera looks to drive but gets beaten all ends up.
Fuller ball on middle and leg, Chameera misses his flick and gets hit on the pads. A bit of appeal but the umpire is unmoved.
Back of a length outside off, Hasaranga pushes this one towards cover point for a single.
Shortish ball around off, jags back in sharply after pitching and hits Hasaranga high on his gloves.
A fuller ball, shaping away outside off, Chameera looks to play at it initially but withdraws at the last moment.
Fuller ball outside off, Chameera looks to play at that, but the ball seams away after pitching to miss the outside edge.
Length ball way outside off, Chameera this time leaves it alone.
Length ball outside off, Chameera looks to push at that one, misses it altogether.
Length ball around off, defended back towards the bowler.
Full and wide outside off, Chameera looks to drive without any foot movement. Misses that one.
Change in bowling. Lutho Sipamla returns. 6-1-25-0 so far. He would love to be in the thick of the action as well.
Short again, this time around off, Hasaranga has no problems in ducking that.
A bumper to follow up a fuller ball, but on middle and leg, easily ducked by Wanindu.
FOUR! Nicely played! A length ball around off, Hasaranga guides this in the gap between third slip and gully to get a boundary.
Fuller length outside off, Hasaranga looks to drive but gets an outside edge towards gully. The fielder does well to stop that.
Shortish around off, Hasaranga looks to play it on the off side, but plays back on his pads.
Length ball around off, played it towards cover.
A length ball around middle, Hasaranga flicks it towards mid-wicket and calls his partner for a quick run to keep strike.
FOUR! Classy drive! A fuller ball around middle, Wanindu stands tall and pushes this one past mid on for a boundary.
Length around off, blocked on the off side.
Close run! A shorter ball around off, played towards point and they take a quick run.

4 LEG BYES! A short ball down the leg side, Chameera looks to tuck but is beaten by pace. The ball hits his thigh pad, just misses the glove, hits the arm guard, one guesses and lobs well over de Kock, to the fine leg fence.
Back of a length outside off, Waanindu plays it with soft hands towards cover and takes a run.
Shortish around off, blocked on the leg side.
FOUR! Back-to-back fours! A shortish ball around middle, Chameera tucks it towards fine leg for a boundary.
FOUR! Short and wide outside off, Chameera flashes and flashes hard. The ball goes above gully towards the third man fence.
A length ball around off, Chameera gets behind and defends it back.
Shortish around leg, Chameera looks to tuck but gets an outside egde towards the slips.
FOUR! A length ball around off, Chameera plays it through the covers for a boundary. That was in the air slightly, but well wide of the fielders.
Lungi Ngidi is back on. 7-3-25-0 so far.
Full and down the leg side, flicked to fine leg for a single.

EDGED, NO ONE THERE, FOUR! Brute of a ball. On a length, outside off, Chameera pushes  at it but the ball rises steeply. The outside edge is taken but it flies right between third slip and gully, to the third man fence.
Another cracker. Pitched on a length, outside off, the ball seams through, as Dushmantha looks to defend, with a massive gap between bat and pad. Goes over the stumps to the keeper.
Short in length, outside off, DC initially looks to play, then tries to duck, in the end does neither completely and the ball shaves past his helmet.

That is a jaffa. A length ball, outside off, Chameera looks to defend but does so inside the line. The ball follows him though, going in between the inside edge and his body, over the stumps and through to de Kock. The bat did not quite come down hard, else he would have nicked it.
Full and outside off, coming in, stays low, well blocked out.
Outside off, Wanindu plays a flashy shot and is beaten.
Around off, angling in, worked through square leg for a single.
Outside off, flayed through point for a run.
Full and outside off, Hasaranga drives this straight back but it is well stopped.
On a length, outside off, punched behind cover for a couple.
Outside off, left alone.
A bouncer, around off, ducked under.
Dushmantha Chameera walks out now.
EDGED AND ANOTHER ONE GONE! Or is it? Shanaka has been given out but he has taken a review. He shakes his head while talking to Hasaranga. Oh dear. Big noise and massive spike on UltraEdge.

OUT! CAUGHT BY THE KEEPER! The decision stays. Wonder why did he take the review. Full and outside off, Shanaka looked to drive but missed. Now, there was a noise as the ball went past and umpire Marais Erasmus raised his finger. Shanaka immediately reviewed, denying that he had nicked it. But then, when replays came, we did hear the noise and UltraEdge showed a massive spike. The freefall continues.
Full on middle, pushed towards mid on.
Good single. Wanindu lunges, pushes this towards cover and sets off for a quick single. Makes it through easily.
This one comes back in a long way, Hasaranga looks to defend but is caught in the crease and hit on the pads.
Back of a length, outside off, punched back to the bowler.
Full and down the leg side, Dasun misses his tuck and is hit on the pads.
Outside off, on a length, moving away, Shanaka shoulders arms.
Outside off, on a length, straightening a touch, let through.
Outside off, Mulder goes wider, this time Dasun does not go chasing.
Outside off, Shanaka plays a loose shot, away from his body and misses.
Fuller and around off, gentle outswinger, watchfully defended.

Outside off, DS looks to defend but the ball goes off the outside edge. The ball goes along the ground but Faf du Plessis manages to stop it with his right hand. Half-stops it. Keeps the batsmen to a single.
Around middle, pushed towards mid on.
Outside off, on a length, angling away, left alone.
Better shot but better fielding. Full and outside off, Dasun drives this to the left of the bowler but Nortje quickly gets across to his left, slides and cuts it off.
Full and outside off, moving away, Shanaka pushes it back to the bowler.
Full and outside off, moving away, Shanaka pushes inside the line and misses.
FOUR! Cracking shot. Shorter from Mulder, outside off, Hasaranga camps back and cuts it through point!
FOUR! That is beautifully played. Not quite a half volley, around off, but Hasaranga comes forward and whips it through mid-wicket.
Fuller and around off, worked through mid-wicket for a couple. SRI LANKA GET TO 100. But way too many wickets lost.
Around off, on a length, worked to the leg side.
Outside off, moving away, left alone.
Outside off, pushed through the covers for a single.
FOUR! ELEGANT! Not a bad way to get off the mark. Overpitched, outside off, Hasaranga leans and drives it through the covers.
Wanindu Hasaranga walks in now, to join the music.

OUT! CAUGHT BY THE KEEPER! Number 6 goes. Nortje has his third. Poor choice of a shot. Just the second over after the break. And Dickwella cannot resist the temptation to drive. It is full and it is wide outside off. Normally, you do drive these balls but only after you are set. Not if they are so wide, so early in your innings. Because normally, so early, your feet don't move. That is what happens with Dickwella too. His feet don't move. The ball does. So does de Kock. He flies to his left to take the outside edge, reverse-cupping his gloves, right in front of first slip.
On a length, outside off, hits a puff of dust, shoots low and goes through to the keeper.
Around middle, keeps low a touch, Niroshan dead-bats it.
Full and outside off, Dickwella look to drive but misses.
Landed outside off, watchfully defended.
Outside off, on a length, shouldered arms to.
Around middle, flicked through mid-wicket for a couple.
Full and outside off, Dickwella pushes it through mid off. No fielder there and the batsmen get three runs.
Full and around off, watchfully defended.
Down the leg side, flick shot missed.
FOUR! Not a bad way to resume post Lunch. Outside off, on a length, Dickwella steers this behind point and gets a boundary!
Welcome back for the afternoon session. Dasun Shanaka has joined Dickwella in the middle. Mulder to continue post Lunch.
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

South Africa will love to see Wiaan Mulder bowl more. At the same time, they would want to take care of his workload as well. He has come into this Test series without much bowling in the domestic 4-day games and has done well in both games so far. He has taken 3 wickets in 3 overs and would be keen to wreck this innings apart. Join us back at 12.40 pm local (1040 GMT) for the second session.

71/1 at one stage, became 84/5, with a wicket falling on the last ball of the session. That is 4 wickets for 13 runs in the span of 23 balls. It was a nightmare for the Lankans, as the Proteas found consistency to their bowling and reaped rewards. The visitors simply did not have time to adjust and their technical flaws were brought out. On bouncy tracks, batsmen with a not-so-good-technique are found wanting. They have lost half their side, which is the bulk of their batting and don't have enough batsmen left. Yes, Dickwella, Shanaka and Hasaranga can bat, but the Lankans will look back at this period and say, what if - what if Lunch had been called half an hour earlier.

South Africa would be happily going into the break. They were staring at a very rough opening session, because apart from the wicket of Dimuth Karunaratne, who got a snorter, they had nothing much. Kusal Perera was chancing his arm and it was coming off. South Africa were got off their consistency. They were getting their lengths and lines good on certain occasions but not consistently enough. And then, Kusal gave a gift. He threw his wicket away and the floodgates opened.

Ouch. My fingers. I was yawning for the first half an hour. Then got jolted into reality by Kusal Perera's counter-attack. And in the last half an hour, well, my eyes have really popped out. What a session of cricket. Enthralling. Thrilling.

OUT! CAUGHT AT SLIP AGAIN! Nightmare. In broad daylight. Another one goes. Perhaps Bhanuka got a bit overconfident, after his previous boundary. It is a similar ball too. On a length again and angling away. But this one has extra bounce. As a result, Bhanuka is not quite able to get on top of the bounce. He ends up fishing outside off and gets a thick outside edge. The ball continues to climb even after taking the edge and Rassie van der Dussen at first slip leaps to complete the formalities. LUNCH ON DAY 1!
FOUR! First boundary for the debutant. On a length, outside off, Bhanuka punches this through the line, gets on top of the bounce and punches it past the diving backward point fielder, to his left.
Outside off, on a length, angling away, shouldered arms to.
Back of a length delivery outside off, let through.
Full and around middle, shaping in a touch, pushed back to the bowler.
A short ball, tucked to the leg side.
Around middle, dabbed to the leg side.
Niroshan Diickwella walks in now, at number 6, replacing Thirimanne.

OUT! CAUGHT AT SLIP! When is Lunch? When is Lunch? This is what Sri Lanka would be asking. It has been a torrid last few minutes for them. 3 wickets for 9 runs in 17 balls! The slip cordon is back in action. A length ball, around middle, Thirimanne looks to work it to the leg side, but the ball moves away, squares him up, takes the outside edge and goes low. But Faf du Plessis adjusts well at second slip adjusts well to get low and forward and take it.
Full and outside off, Lahiru looks to defend initially, but then takes his bat away.
Gets off the mark. A length ball, around middle and leg, flicked towards square leg for a single.
Outside off, shaping away, left alone.
Around middle and leg, Bhanuka looks to tuck it to the leg side but gets an inside edge onto his pads.
Around off, a tight, compact defense is on offer.
Risky shot. Around middle and off, coming in, Lahiru guides it with an angled bat face towards the slip cordon. It was more of an angled defensive shot. Not advisable in this case. Or any case.

FOUR! 'Oh... yes...' goes Pommie Mbangwa on air. What a shot.  Short and outside off, Thirimanne gets high on his toes, with his left leg in the air and using the pace of Nortje, crashes it aerially through point.
Around middle and leg, helped towards square leg.
On a length, around middle and leg, Lahiru looks to defend but the ball moves away off the deck, squares him up and beats the outside edge.
FOUR! CRISP! Full and outside off, Thirimanne lunges and drives. Extra cover, who is actually standing at wide mid off, dives to his left but the ball goes through.
Around middle and leg, tucked to the leg side.
Lunch watchman? Ha ha, nothing like that, is there, in cricket? Who has come in, with 12 minutes to go to Lunch? It is the debutant, Minod Bhanuka.

OUT! EDGED TO SLIP! Mendis walked in and now Mendis has walked out. A so, so, so Kusal Mendis out. Pitch the ball around off, on a fuller length, get him to drive or defend and eke out the outside edge. In this case, it was the latter. On a length, around middle, Mendis looks to defend but the ball just shapes away a touch and squares him up. Mendis is in no position to adjust and plays with an open bat face, with the edge carrying comfortably to Rassie van der Dussen at first slip.
On a length, outside off, pushed towards point.
Outside off, on a length, quietly left alone.

EDGED, SHORT! Oohh... things are happening. On a length, outside off, Mendis looks to defend but the ball moves away a touch, takes the outside edge. Now, because he played with soft hands, the edge does not carry to third slip.
Kusal Mendis is the next man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Once again, Wiaan Mulder gets the wicket of Kusal Perera! Big wicket for South Africa but Kusal Perera will be disappointed with this shot. He was looking so good but now has to depart. He was looking fidgety since he got to his fifty but now has perished. Mulder bowls a good length ball outside off, Perera looks to drive but it takes the outside edge and it goes towards Markram at gully who makes no mistake.
Good length ball outside off, Thirimanne shoulders arms to this one.
Full ball outside off, Thirimanne drives it through the covers for a couple of runs.
Fullish ball on off, Lahiru pushes it towards mid off.
Fullish ball on middle, Lahiru works it to mid-wicket.
Outside off, left alone by Lahiru.

DROPPED! Dean Elgar is the culprit! An opportunity was created but not taken by South Africa. This should have been taken at this level. Good length ball outside off, Thirimanne looks to defend but it takes the outside edge and it goes towards third slip. Elgar moves down but fails to hold on.
Good length ball on middle, Perera defends it out off the back foot.
Back of a length ball on off, Kusal taps it towards point.
Good length ball around off, Perera looks to heave it away but it takes the inside edge and goes towards mid on.
Full ball down the leg side, Perera looks to flick but misses. There is a mild appeal for caught behind but the umpire is not interested.
Back of a length ball on middle, defended back to the bowler.
Fullish ball on middle and leg, Perera defends it towards mid on off the front foot.
Wiaan Mulder comes into bowl now. He replaces Lutho Sipamla.
Full ball on off, Thirimanne defends it to cover.
50-run stand comes up! Shortish ball on middle and leg, Perera works it to fine leg for a single. It has taken just 48 balls. Perera has contributed 43 while Thirimanne has contributed just 7.
Short ball outside off, Perera looks to pull but fails to get any bat on it.
FOUR! Mowed! Perera will keep on attacking. Full ball outside off, Perera mows it through the mid-wicket region for a boundary.
Very full ball outside off, Thirmanne digs it out towards the cover region for a single.
Sloppy fielding! Fullish ball on off, Perera pushes it to cover where Bavuma misfields, allowing the batters to cross for a single.
On middle, tucked to mid-wicket.
Good length ball on the pads, Kusal works it to deep square leg for a single.
Full on off, Perera pushes it to mid off.

FOUR! FIFTY! 6th Test fifty for Kusal Perera! He has got it in just 54 balls. He loves playing in South Africa and continues his good form. Good length ball on middle, Perera whips it to deep square leg where the fielder comes across but fails to stop it.
Good length ball on middle, Lahiru works it to the leg side for a single.
Back of a length ball around off, Thirimanne looks to defend at first but then decides to leave it alone.
Ngidi comes around the wicket and bowls a short one on middle, Perera works it to deep square leg for a couple. Moves to 49.
FOUR! This is quality batting from Kusal Perera! Ngidi overpitches this one on middle, Perera powers it through mid on for a boundary.
FOUR! Great shot from Kusal Perera! Full ball on off, Perera drives it past Ngidi. It hits Thirmimanne's bat at the other end and it still has enough to go to the long off fence. 50 up for Sri Lanka.
Full ball on middle, pushed back to the bowler.
PLAY AND A MISS! Full ball outside off, Perera looks for the extravagant drive but fails to make any connection.
Full ball down the leg side, Perera looks to flick but misses it altogether.
BEATEN! Lovely piece of bowling from Sipamla! Good length ball outside off, Thirimanne looks to defend but the ball beats the outside edge.
On off, Thirimanne blocks it to cover and says no for the single.
Full ball on middle, Lahiru defends it back to the bowler.
Back of a length ball on middle, Kusal works it to mid-wicket for a single.

Some miscommunication! Good length ball on middle, Perera works it to the side of the pitch on the leg side. Perera wants the single but Thirimanne is not at all interested and sends him back. Sipamla rushes in and has a shy at the keeper's end but misses.
FOUR! Slapped! Perera is looking in positive touch! Full ball outside off, Perera smacks it over the mid off fielder for a boundary. Perera moves to 38 off just 45 balls.
Back of a length ball around middle, Perera looks to flick but it goes off his gloves towards fine leg for a single.
FOUR! Up and over! Perera will not miss out on these! Shortish ball outside off, Perera whacks it over the cover region for a boundary.
BEATEN! That's the area where Ngidi has to bowl more often! Good length ball around off, Perera pokes at it but the ball goes past his outside edge and it goes to the keeper.
Good length ball on middle, Perera defends it to mid on.
Back of a length ball down the leg side, Perera leaves it alone.
Fullish ball on off, Thirimanne works it to the mid-wicket region for a single. First run off Ngidi's bowling.
Change of ends for Lungi Ngidi. 3-3-0-0 are his figures so far.

Drinks! South Africa have bowled well so far. Ngidi was right on the money while Nortje was exceptional with his lines and lengths. He was rewarded with the wicket of Dimuth Karunaratne. They though will feel a little unlucky that they could not find more edges. Sri Lanka, on the other hand, won't mind as they have survived the first few overs and have lost just one wicket. Kusal Perera has looked positive while Dimuth looked good before he departed. They would hope to consolidate after the break.
Good length ball on off, Perera defends it to cover-point.
Full ball outside off, Perera pushes it to cover.
Low full toss on middle, Perera flicks it through mid-wicket and picks up a couple.
Full ball outside off, Perera drives but finds the cover fielder.
Short ball outside off, Perera looks to pull off the back foot but misses.
PLAY AND A MISS! Good length ball outside off, Perera throws the kitchen sink at it but fails to make any connection.
Back of a length ball on middle, Thirimanne hops and works it to the leg side.
Outside off, left alone.

Big shout for LBW turned down! Good length ball on middle and leg, Thirimanne looks to defend but misses and gets rapped on the pads. Nortje puts in a huge appeal for LBW but the umpire is unmoved. Quinton de Kock signals that it might be going over so no review.
Fullish ball on middle, Lahiru defends it back to the bowler.
FOUR! Thirimanne is off the mark in a beautiful fashion! Back of a length ball on the pads, Lahiru flicks it through square leg for a boundary.
Full ball on off, Lahiru defends it to cover.
Good length ball outside off, Perera leaves it alone.
FOUR! Easy pickings for Perera! Full ball on the pads, Perera flicks it through square leg. Nortje comes across from fine leg and puts in a dive but in vain. A boundary signaled.
Fullish ball on middle, Perera defends it back to the bowler.
Good length ball on the pads, Perera looks to flick but it goes off his pads, past the diving keeper towards fine leg. Two runs taken. Runs given so must have hit the bat.

FOUR! Poor delivery! Shortish ball down the leg side, Perera pulls it to fine leg. The fielder there had no idea where the ball is and he moved to his right while the ball was on his left. It goes to the fence.
Back of a length ball on off, Perera stands tall and then blocks it off the back foot.
Ohh, what a ball from Nortje! Perfect delivery to a new batsman. Good length ball around off, angling in. Thirimanne looks to defend but it goes in between his bat and pad, towards the keeper.
Lahiru Thirimanne comes out to bat at no.3.

OUT! CAUGHT! Nortje was testing Sri Lanka since his opening over and he finally gets his reward! This is terrific bowling from Nortje. Terrific result for Nortje and South Africa. He runs in and bowls a back of a length ball around off, it zips after pitching. Karunaratne looks to defend off the back foot but it takes the outside edge and goes towards de Kock. He makes no mistake. Anrich Nortje deserves this wicket. He has bowled brilliantly so far.
Fullish ball on middle, Dimuth works it to mid-wicket.
Good length ball on off, Karunaratne looks to defend but it takes the outside edge and it rolls to the gully fielder.
On off, Kusal punches it towards the cover region for a single.
BEATEN! Lovely stuff from Nortje! Good length ball around off, Perera looks to defend but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Good length ball on the pads, Perera looks to flick but it takes the inside edge, hits the pads and goes to fine leg for a single.
Shortish ball on off, Dimuth stands tall and then pushes it through cover-point for a single.
Back of a length ball on middle and leg, Dimuth looks to play the flick shot but once again gets hit on the thigh pad.
Good length ball on middle and leg, Dimuth looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the thigh pad. Good from Sipamla so far.

A mild appeal for LBW turned down! Fullish ball on the pads, Karunaratne looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads. There is an appeal for LBW but the umpire shakes his head. Probably going down leg.
Short ball outside off, Karunaratne punches it to point.
More sawdust is being brought on and being put on the bowler's crease.
FOUR! CREAMED! Poor delivery from Nortje! He bowls a half-volley outside off, Perera gleefully accepts it as he creams the drive through the cover region for a boundary.
Shortish ball on middle, Perera defends it to mid off from the back foot.
Karunaratne is off the mark off his 24th delivery! Back of a length ball on middle, Dimuth hops and tucks it to the square leg region for a single.
Hits the pads! On a length ball on the pads, Karunaratne looks to defend but it hits the pads. There is a mild appeal for LBW but nothing from the umpire.
Good length ball outside off, Karunaratne watches the ball carefully and then leaves it alone.
Nortje bowls a full ball on off, Karunaratne is still not off the mark as he defends it towards the leg side.

Now, now, now, what happened? The physio has come running out to the middle. Has Perera hurt himself? Yeah, on that last ball. Nothing much done and the physio is off too. But he does not look that comfortable, does KP.
OUCH. That has kicked off. A short ball, outside leg, Perera looks to pull but the steep bounce does him in. Takes the top edge and hits him on the chest.
Another beauty. On a length, outside off, angling away, Perera plays inside the line and is beaten again. Something has been said to him by Karunaratne, as both exchange smiles.
A short ball, helped towards square leg.

IN THE AIR... SAFE! First real opportunity all morning. Full and around middle, Perera looks to work it to the leg side but the ball skids through, squares him up, takes the leading edge and pops up in the air. Extra cover gets across to his left but cannot reach. The ball drops short.
A length ball, down the leg side, Kusal looks to help it fine but the ball hits the glove and lands on the bounce. Does not go too far. De Kock gets to it. Kusal wants the single but is sent back.
Immediately, Sipamla call for sawdust to be sprayed on the landing area. The landing of the foot is a problem, with just a little bit of slipping going on.
A short ball, down the leg side, Perera looks to pull but misses it completely.

Lutho Sipamla is into the attack now. Someone goes off the field, as we see Sarel Erwee substituting.  One reckons it is Lungi Ngidi. Yeah, my colleague confirms. Thanks to him for that, clearly showing quietly who is more attentive... just a bit of a strapping of the shoes, one guesses. Ngidi was not happy with it in the last over.
Pitched up, outside off, angling away, Karunaratne looks to defend, then aims to withdraw his bat but we can call it as beaten.
Around off, on a length, pushed to the off side.

This is delivered with a normal upright seam. But the length is problematic for Kusal. It seems like a normal good length ball, but the ball pitches and skids on, hitting the splice of the bat. Perera pushes it towards cover and calls his skipper through for the single.

Scrambled seam again, landed on back of a length, around middle, Kusal looks to tuck it to the leg side but the ball skids on, beats him for room, takes the inside edge, hits the pads and rolls to the leg side.
FOUR! No indecision on this one! A short ball, wide outside off, Perera latches onto this, leaps and cuts it over cover.

No idea at all. This is back of a length and around leg. Kusal looks to whip it to the leg side but the ball nips back in and he looks to abort. Good decision in the end. The ball hits him on the left thigh. Quick decision taken to back out.
Landed outside off, shouldered arms to.
Full again, outside off, DK comes forward and defends.
Fuller length now, outside off, Dimuth gets across and shoulders arms.

A short ball, outside off, Karunaratne looks to pull but the ball skids on, beats him, takes the inside edge, deflects onto the pads and then lobs to the on side. First real shot of aggression from the skipper.
Around middle, coming in, played off the inner half of the bat towards mid on.
A length ball, outside off, left alone. That looked like an off spinner, pitching and then moving away slowly. One suspects that it was bowled with a scrambled seam.

That is the line and length. Fuller, around the stumps, KP looks to tuck it to the leg side but the away angle squares him up. Induces an outside edge which does not carry to Rassie van der Dussen at gully.
Nortje now holds his length back, makes this to angle across the left-hander, KP plays inside the line, looking to defend but is beaten.
A length ball wide outside off, Kusal throws his bat at it but misses.
Another cracking delivery. This one kicks off the deck, KP looks to tuck it to the leg side but the extra bounce does him in. The inside edge is eked out and the ball rolls past the leg stump.
A nasty delivery. On a length, around middle, swinging in, Perera looks to tuck it to the leg side but is cramped for room. The ball goes off the body towards gully.

That is a good ball. South Africa need to make the new ball count. The ball beats the outside edge and Nortje shakes his head. Not because of the ball missing the edge, but because of his landing area. He is not happy at all. He is bowling at 128 kph, when he normally is at 145. This was on a length, outside leg, Kusal looked to prod but missed.
Nortje adjusts the sawdust around the landing area.
Outside off again, moving away slightly, let through for de Kock to collect.

Yes, that is it. Keep it full, keep it full, invite the batsman for a drive on a lazy Sunday morning and hope that he nicks. From Sri Lanka's point of view, yes, yes, show patience, show patience and stay indoors, not going out for a drive. Left alone.

Beauty! That is a good line. What about the length? Awesome. Just short of a fuller length, draws the batsman forward. Now, because he bowled that with a scrambled seam, the ball bounces and shapes away, beating the outside edge. Now, to be consistent with this length and line.
Back of a length, outside off, rising awkwardly, Karunaratne rises with the bounce and pushes it towards cover.
Full and outside off, swinging away, Karunaratne shoulders arms. The struggle for the South Africans is going to be how to keep it consistently full.
On a length, around off, left alone.
The sawdust does come out.

FOUR! STUPENDOUS! There goes Kusal! You never can keep him out from driving if you bowl full. This is wide as well. Extra invitation. Kusal leans and hammers it, ala Sanath Jayasuriya, over cover. The first boundary of the game.
OUCH. That would have hurt. On a length, around middle, Kusal looks to tuck but misses and is hit on the body, via an inside edge.
Outside off, angling away, let through.
Issues for Nortje? He is not quite happy with the way he landed after that previous ball. Turns back, looks at the landing area and perhaps asks for some sawdust. Nothing urgent.
A short ball, down the leg side, Perera takes his hand away from the ball.
Full and outside off, immediately Kusal looks to drive but misses.
Outside off, a half volley, driven wide of mid off for a couple. The Lankan innings gets underway.

Anrich Nortje it is, to share the new ball with Ngidi. My colleague, who is closely monitoring Sri Lankan cricket, informs me that Nortje did not start off with Ngidi in the last game. It was Lutho Sipamla. Which explains why Anrich was standing at short mid-wicket. Apologies for missing out.
A length ball, outside off, interesting from DK, as he walks into the shot. Is the ball not quite coming on? Left alone. Interesting maiden.
Back of a length, outside off, DK shoulders arms.

Ooohh.... full and around off, Dimuth looks to drive. But the ball just straightens a touch and the bat face closes a bit early this time. The ball takes the inner half of the bat and goes to Anrich Nortje at short mid-wicket. What is he doing there? Won't he be sharing the new ball?
Outside off again, let through once more.
On a length, outside off, good carry through to the keeper, as the skipper shoulders arms.
On a length, around off, coming in, Karunaratne plays it with a closed bat-face to the leg side.

Right. The national anthems are done and we are ready for play. South Africa's assistant coach, Enoch Nkwe, rings the bell and we are ready. Has become a fashion these days, aye? Normally, the bell used to be rung primarily at Lord's. Good to see it becoming a fashion. Dimuth Karunaratne and Kusal Perera are the openers for the Lankans. Lungi Ngidi will start off proceedings, to the Lankan skipper. Here we go...
The two teams are out in the middle for the national anthems. NAMO NAMO NAMO MATHA first up, with Sri Lanka being the visiting team.

Wiaan Mulder now, comes up for a talk. Is happy with the win for the team, after all that happened over the previous year. Is personally satisfied as well, to have bowled 32 overs without breaking down. Puts it down to hard work put in the last two years, wherein he has developed more stamina. Admits that he could not bowl as much as he wanted to in the 4-day games prior to the Boxing Day Test, but now, has the confidence to bowl more overs. Believes that this will be a similar pitch to the previous game with the fast bowlers getting help, if they land the ball in the right areas. Stresses that if wickets don't come by, then they need to bowl as many dot balls as they can and make the batsmen commit mistakes.

Niroshan Dickwella is up for a chat. Is disappointed that Sri Lanka could not even compete in the first Test, due to the injuries and hopes to make a comeback in this Test. Stresses that they have been training well, not only before this Test but even before this tour. Admits that they were not quite prepared for the Tests but believes that the team has learnt its lesson. Wants his side to take it session by session. Remembers that in the press conference at the end of the opening day, he had mentioned that Sri Lanka were in the driver's seat but feels unfortunate to be proved wrong. On the keeping in South Africa, with the inconsistent bounce, Dickwella says that he likes the ball to come to him and is eager to be a part of the game.

No surprises to see either of the two teams. South Africa have confidence and gone in with the same XI, resisting the temptation to field Rabada while Sri Lanka basically have had no choice. There has been a lot of talk regarding Minod Bhanuka and Asitha Fernando in the Lankan domestic circuit and it will be exciting to see how they fare at the international level.

South Africa (UNCHANGED Playing XI) - Dean Elgar, Aiden Markram, Rassie van der Dussen, Faf du Plessis, Quinton de Kock (C AND WK), Temba Bavuma, Wiaan Mulder, Keshav Maharaj, Anrich Nortje, Lutho Sipamla and Lungi Ngidi.

Sri Lanka (Playing XI) - Dimuth Karunaratne (C), Kusal Perera, Lahiru Thirimanne (IN FOR DINESH CHANDIMAL), Kusal Mendis, Minod Bhanuka (DEBUT, IN FOR DHANANJAYA DE SILVA), Niroshan Dickwella(w), Dasun Shanaka, Wanindu Hasaranga, Vishwa Fernando, Dushmantha Chameera (IN FOR KASUN RAJITHA) and Asitha Fernando (DEBUT, IN FOR LAHIRU KUMARA).

South African captain, Quinton de Kock, honestly says that there was not much talk about getting Kagiso Rabada back into the side as they want him fit for the Pakistan Tests. On the message to his team after the previous win, de Kock says that the message was just to be ruthless and nothing much, as everyone knows what needs to be done. On his captaincy role, Quinton says that he has not given too much thought about it and needs more time. Hopes to double his wins as a Test captain. Wants to begin 2021 on a good note and get another win under their belt. Also is aware of the World Test Championship and wants to stake a claim. On the opportunity to bat first not given, QdK honestly says that he was not sure what to do on this deck and now wants his bowlers to be on the mark from ball 1.

Sri Lankan skipper, Dimuth Karunaratne, informs about the two debutants (Minod Bhanuka and Asitha Fernando), stressing that they are in because of their talent, rather than being forced in due to injuries to other players. Believes that the conditions here will suit them. Admits that the start-stop training at home, due to Covid could not help them prepare well, but stresses that they are eager to play good cricket and level the series. Honestly says that he does not have his best XI, personally, but has faith in his young team to do well. Feels that the wicket is really good and hopes to get the maximum runs off the pitch when it is good to bat.

TOSS - We are all set for the spin of the coin. The captains are out in the middle - Quinton de Kock and Dimuth Karunaratne. De Kock being the home captain, flips the coin. Tails is the call from Karunaratne and it is a tail. SRI LANKA WILL BAT FIRST. That is a brave call, after what happened in the last Test.

PITCH REPORT - JP Duminy says that if you are a seamer, you will be licking your lips looking at the grass on the surface. There is plenty of it available but also adds that the first hour is the key. After that, he details that the pitch settles down, the ball comes on nicely due to the even covering of the grass and the Wanderers gives you plenty of value for your shots, because of the lush green outfield. Informs that the average score on the opening day of a Test here is 262/7. Expects plenty of gritty cricket.
The medical staff is on the field now, with lot of instructions being given. They will need to be on their toes, especially in these circumstances.

WEATHER - Bright and sunny! Looks to be a great day to be playing cricket. Don't think the weather will have a say but then, I never really sent my resume to the meteorological department, so cannot claim that I am a weather expert. Let's hope we get 5 full days of cricket.

Talking about South Africa, there were plenty of off-field talks, with skipper Quinton de Kock openly stating that he is not looking at captaincy as a long-term option. That sounds negative and it seemed to show in the way the Proteas bowled on Day 1. But from there on, it seemed they were spurred on, with the performance going a notch above. No Kagiso Rabada for this game, with the management deciding to rest him, with a view for the series ahead. South Africa travel to Pakistan and then host Australia, if everything goes as planned. Another opportunity for the young guns to showcase what they have got.

Both South Africa and Sri Lanka began this tour on uncertain terms. Both had their long-term future in doubt, with experienced players stepping away and youngsters taking up the mantle. Sri Lanka bossed Day 1 but since then, a spate of injuries made them being forced into unwanted leaves, with players being ruled out due to injuries. They enter this game no less certain about their playing XI with last-minute calls set to be taken depending on fitness tests.

Happy New Year, happy new year, happy new year! Phew, so much eager and excitement to usher in 2021, ain't there? After all that happened in the previous year, probably it is justified. We are still into the infancy of 2021 but slowy settling down. Cricket has never really stopped, with domestic cricket going all around the globe while international action kicked off a few hours ago with New Zealand playing Pakistan in the second Test. On Day 1, Pakistan have managed 297, thanks to Azhar Ali's 93. Now, it is time to shift to the rainbow nation.

The players have returned on the field! Dimuth Karunaratne and Kusal Perera are the usual openers for Sri Lanka. Lungi Ngidi to begin proceedings from 'round the wicket. Three slips waiting, here we go...

A word of praise for all the Sri Lankan bowlers. It was a hard toil for them on Day 1 but the fightback produced by them was spirited. All the pacers were impressive in their efforts and Vishwa Fernando, with a fifer, emerged as the most successful one. Now then, once again it's come down to the Sri Lankan batting. They were extremely poor in the first stint. Can they put up a better show? Let's find out.

You can call it a very poor batting show by the South African middle and lower order. Apart from the big century stand between Dean Elgar and Rassie van der Dussen, there wasn't much from the rest. Due to that record partnership, South Africa have managed to gain a lead which can be considered to be quite handy on this pitch.

Brilliant turnaround from Sri Lanka! They were down and appeared out as well last evening but have bounced back superbly. In the second hour of the morning, the Lankan bowlers found some rhythm and ran through the African batting line-up. The last wicket did frustrate them for a bit but eventually, Vishwa Fernando picked the final scalp to complete his maiden fifer in Tests.

OUT! CAUGHT! 5 wickets for Vishva Fernando. He has bowled extremely well and thoroughly deserves this 5-fer. A shortish ball around off, Sipamla looks to punch it from the back foot but ends up edging it towards the fielder at gully. Shanaka there jumps and takes a good catch. South Africa are bowled out for 302 and have a lead of 145 runs.
Length ball around middle and off, Sipamla gets behind the line and blocks this out.
Fuller this time on middle, Ngidi drives it towards mid off and collects a quick single.
Shortish around off, angling across, Ngidi sways away from this one and lets it go.

Drinks break. It's good work from the 10th wicket partnership and it's worth 18 runs at the moment. Frustrating for Sri Lanka who have been superb post Lunch. The lead has reached 144 and it's already looking like a massive one. Vishwa Fernando to continue after the break as well. He is eyeing a fifer here...
Effort delivery. Chameera digs in a short ball around off, it zips off the surface and Sipamla sways away from the line.
A length ball around middle and off from 'round the wicket, Sipamla does well to block it to the off side.
A bouncer now, ducked under by Lutho.
Shortish and on off, straightening a bit, Sipamla gets squared up and pushes it out to point. Looks for a run but is sent back.
That is defended solidly off the front foot.
Good length ball on middle, Sipamla tries to defend but it hits him on the splice of the bat.
Dushmantha Chameera (13-0-53-1) is back on.
Bumper to finish off the over. Ducked comfortably by Ngidi.
Shortish ball angling across the batsmen, Ngidi is caught off guard as he somehow manages to play the ball on the off side.
Length ball around middle, Sipamla rocks back and tucks this one towards deep square leg for a single.
Good length ball around leg, Sipamla fails to work it away and is hit high on the front leg.
FOUR! First runs for Sipamla in Test matches. A fuller length ball around off, Sipamla drives it through the covers to get himself a boundary. 300 up for South Africa now.
Length ball on middle, Sipamla stands firm and defends this on the pitch.
And again! Ngidi is flashing his bat but connecting only with thin air. Short and outside off, Ngidi attempts again for the pull shot but misses.
Swing and a miss! Short and around off, Ngidi tries to pull but fails to make any connection.
A bouncer this time but down the leg side, second for the over. Easy leave for Lungi.
Short again, on middle and leg, Ngidi tries to play the pull shot but fails to connect.
A touch short and outside off, Ngidi moves away from the line.
The physio comes out to conduct a mandatory concussion check. Ngidi is smiling and checking his helmet.
Bang on the helmet! Asitha digs in a bouncer, well-directed, Ngidi tries to duck but it hits him on the helmet and balloons in the air. The bowler catches it and appeals. Nothing from the umpire.
Fullish around off, driven straight to mid off by Sipamla.
Angles in a length ball on off, Ngidi tries to heave it on the leg side but gets a leading edge towards mid off. They cross for a brisk run as the fielder misses his shy at the bowler's end.

SAFE! It's a bump ball. Fuller ball on middle, Ngidi hits it straight back to the bowler. Fernando appeals for a catch and the umpires go upstairs. Replays show the ball to be bouncing before going to the bowler. Not out is the signal from the third umpire.
Shout for a caught and bowled! The two umpires get together and then decide to take it upstairs. Is that a bump ball? Yup, it is.
Play and a miss! A length ball outside off, Nigidi tries to smash that on the leg side but connects only with thin air.

FOUR! Back-to-back boundaries. A short ball from Fernando on Ngidi's body. He tries to move away but the ball hits the top part of the bat and runs towards the boundary over the slips. Handy runs these for the Proteas.

FOUR! Driven nicely. A fuller length around middle, Ngidi punches this one with a straight bat past the bowler and the fielder at mid on and collects his second four. Quinton de Kock flashes a smile in the dressing room. The lead moves to 134.
Back of a length ball on off, Sipamla goes on the back foot and pushes it to short cover.
Good length in the channel outside off, Sipamla shoulders arms. Has looked assured so far.
Asitha mixes his length seeing Sipamla getting comfortable with the pitched up deliveries. Bangs in a bouncer on middle, Lutho ducks.
Three blocks in a row. Very solid as well from Sipamla. Dealing with the full balls well.
Once again Lutho covers the line and defends it with a straight bat.
Fullish and off, Sipamla defends it off the front foot to mid off.
A length ball angling in from around off, Ngidi defends it back from the crease.
FOUR! Shot! That's smacked. Fuller and on off, Ngidi drills his drive through wide mid off and opens his account with a boundary.
Jaffa! A length ball on middle and off, Ngidi tries to play it with a straight bat but misses. It goes over the stumps.
Lungi Ngidi is the last batsman.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! 9 down are South Africa. A length ball around off, straightens after pitching. Nortje is in two minds whether to defend or leave and ends up edging it towards second slip where Kusal Mendis takes a good catch over his head. Vishwa has four and kisses the turf to celebrate it.
Fuller ball around off, Nortje does well to block it out straight towards the bowler, who uses his feet to stop the ball. Nice bit of footwork by Vishwa.
FOUR! Nicely played. A length ball around off, Nortje guides this one to the right of the gully fielder and the outfield does the rest as the ball races away towards the third man fence.
Softly plays it in the gap at covers and retains strike with a run.
Back of a length ball on off, Anrich jumps on the back foot and defends it to point.
A length ball outside off, dabbed down from the crease to point.
That is left alone for the keeper to collect.
The batsman has just watchfully blocked this out.
On a length and outside off, pushed to covers for a risky second run.
Lutho Sipamla is the new batsman.

DRS time! Bavuma has misjudged one delivery and decided not to offer any shot. He is rapped on the pads, the appeal is made and the umpire feels that it's curving back in enough to hit the stumps. The finger goes up and Bavuma takes the referral...

OUT! It's crashing into the stumps and South Africa lose another wicket. Vishwa has his third and he is all pumped up. He dishes out a beautiful delivery, an inswinger on a length outside off, Bavuma decides to offer no shot and takes it on his pads. Not sure whether he expected the ball to nip back in so much. As soon as he is struck on the pads, the bowler appeals and the umpire lifts his finger. Temba takes the DRS but it is of no use. No shot offered, so the impact cannot be an issue and the ball is hitting the middle stump. All over for the little man.
FOUR! Lovely drive. A fullish ball around middle, Bavuma drives this nicely towards mid on. The fielder there slips and allows the ball to go through his legs.
Back of a length outside off, Bavuma pushes it towards gully and starts running, but returns back as his partner says a loud 'NO'.
Short of a length around middle, Bavuma hops and defends it on the on side.
Fullish again around middle and leg, Anrich flicks this one towards deep square leg for a run.
Fuller length drifting on the pads, Anrich looks to flick but misses and the ball lobs to the left of the keeper.
In the channel outside off, Bavuma makes a safe leave.
EDGED BUT SAFE! Shortish and outside off, Nortje flashes his bat it and gets it away off the toe end. It dies in front of the keeper and sneaks past the slip cordon. A single is taken.
Back of a length ball on off, Anrich goes on the back foot and taps it down to point.
Fullish and around off, Nortje covers the line and pushes it towards cover.

EDGY FOUR! Valuable runs for South Africa, the lead moves to 113! Good length ball is angled into the batsman, it straightens from outside off, Anrich pushes at it and edges it between third slip and gully for a boundary.
Pitches it up and wide outside off, shaping away, Nortje allows it through.
Beauty! A length ball around off, shapes away sharply after pitching and beats Bavuma's outside edge by a very little margin. Sri Lanka right on the money after Lunch here.
Length around middle, Bavuma blocks this out on the on side.
Length ball around off, Bavuma drives it straight to mid off.
DROPPED AND FOUR! Almost another one! A shortish length outside off, Bavuma hits it on the up and the edge goes straight towards gully who lets it go through his hands. Rash shot this by Bavuma.
Length bal around middle, Bavuma gets inside the line and tucks it towards mid-wicket.
Fuller length around middle, comes back in after pitching, Bavuma plays it towards mid-wicket.
Anrich Nortje walks in next.

OUT! This was always on the cards! Asitha keeps on probing with a length delivery around off, Keshav once again has a loose push inside the line and the away movement takes the outside edge to the keeper. Dickwella makes no mistake and South Africa lose their second wicket after Lunch.
Great speed from Asitha. He gets a length ball around off to skid straight on after landing, once again it beats the hanging bat of Keshav.
Beautiful delivery, just around off on a fuller length, nipping way, Maharaj is forward to poke inside the line and misses.
This one is angled on the off stump line, Keshav is forced to defend it to the off side.
Asitha gets closer to the off stump line with his outswinger, Maharaj covers his stumps and shoulders arms.
A gentle loosener, on a length and wide outside off, although there is some pronounced seam movement. Maharaj leaves.
Asitha Fernando to bowl from the other end.
Length ball around off, Maharaj looks to drive, but inside edges it towards square leg and takes a run. Good first over this after Lunch for Sri Lanka.
Fuller ball on middle, Bavuma flicks it towards the gap at mid-wicket and the batsmen take three more before the fielder returns the ball back.
Fuller ball angling across Bavuma, he tries to drive but some late movement takes the inside edge of the bat towards square leg.
Length ball drifting on the pads, Maharaj tucks it towards fine leg and gets off the mark with a single.
Keshav Maharaj is the new batsman.

OUT! LBW! Sri Lanka strike early after Lunch. A low full toss on leg stump, Mulder misses his flick and gets hit on the pads. Huge appeal by the Sri Lankan players and the umpire obliges. Mulder takes the review, but the replay shows that the point of impact is with the umpire's call and also it's once again the umpire's call on hitting the stumps. The original decision stays.

Time for the referral! Mulder has missed a full toss and gets rapped on the pads. The appeal is entertained and the finger has gone up. Is the impact outside the line of leg stump? It's umpire's call on impact and also on hitting the stumps. Mulder departs.
Fernando starts with a shortish ball on the body, Bavuma tucks it towards fine leg for a single. Lead is now 100!

Back for the afternoon session! This Test match is still tilted in favour of South Africa and that's why Sri Lanka cannot afford to relax. The tourists will have to limit the damage here and restrict the lead to as low as possible. Temba Bavuma and Wiaan Mulder are ready to resume. Here is Vishwa Fernando...
.....DAY 2, SECOND SESSION.....

From the point of view of this Test match and looking at the spicy nature of this pitch, South Africa already have a handy lead. But they won't like to bat last on this surface and hence would be looking for a big lead. Bavuma and Mulder are the last recognized pair for them but the batsmen to follow have shown some ability. A lead close to 150 will be something in the South African agenda currently. Will they get there? Do join us at 12.40 pm local (1040 GMT) for the second session to find out.

Dushmantha Chameera bagged the prized scalp of Dean Elgar and that gave Sri Lanka a slight opening. The tourists barged into it and managed to force a collapse. Rassie, Faf and Quinton fell in quick succession and it was a period of complete mayhem for the home team. From a position of dominance, they lost the plot completely and are now five wickets down with a lead of 99.

What a session for Sri Lanka! Initially, it appeared to be the repeat telecast of last evening as South Africa dominated the first hour. Dean Elgar and Rassie van der Dussen batted positively and took South Africa into the lead. Then, the Drinks break came and post that the picture changed completely.
FOUR! Classy drive! A fuller ball on middle, Mulder leans into the shot and drives it nicely straight down the ground. With that, it's Lunch on Day 2.
Slightly short and wide outside off, Mulder throws his bat at that but gets the bottom edge and the ball rolls over towards second slip. A bit of misfield but no run is taken.
Length ball around off, Mulder pushes this one towards covers.
Length ball in the channel outside off, left alone.
Length ball around off, Bavuma plays it softly towards cover-point and takes a quick run.
That is defended solidly off the front foot.
Jumps down the track to a full ball and bunts it to mid on. End of the over, Sri Lanka are doing a nice job.
Fullish again, around off, this time Temba eases it to covers for a run.
Fullish and on off, defended towards the mid off region.
The line remains too straight and it's turned behind square leg for one. Given as a leg bye. 250 up for South Africa!
Drifting down the leg side, Mulder lets it be. There is a leg gully in place. So, they are definitely working on a plan.
On middle and leg, Bavuma works it with the angle to square leg for a run.
Length ball outside off, this time Mulder keeps his bat away from the ball and lets it go.
That is the length Mr Shanaka. A length ball around off, shapes away and beats Mulder's outside edge by not much.
Fuller ball outside off, Mulder drives this past the covers but doesn't have the timing to reach the boundary. He comes back for a brace.
FOUR LEG BYES! Shanaka overcorrects his line, it's pushed down on middle and leg, Mulder looks to tuck but gets hit on the pads and the ball races away towards the fine leg fence.
Fullish length outside off, shapes away after pitching, Mulder is not interested in playing that.
Fuller ball inviting the drive outside off, Mulder is happy to let it go.
Back of a length ball angling down the leg side, Bavuma fails to glance it across the line.
Angling into the batsman, from 'round the wicket, a length ball, Bavuma pushes it with an angled bat to point.
Good length ball on middle, Bavuma blocks it to mid-wicket.
Mulder opens his account. Another delivery on the leg stump line, Wiaan eases it through square leg and picks up a run.
Drifting down the leg side, Wiaan tries to flick but fails to get any bat on it.
Good length ball on middle, Mulder defends it towards mid-wicket.
Tight bowling this by Sri Lanka. A length ball around off, Bavuma prods forwards and plays it back to the bowler. A maiden over.
Length around off, Bavuma blocks this out on the off side.
Fuller in the channel outside off, Bavuma leaves it alone.
Closer on middle and leg, Bavuma stands tall and defends it towards mid-wicket.
Again a teasing ball wide outside off, Bavuma is confident in his leave.
Length ball outside off, shapes away after pitching, Bavuma lets it go.
Wiaan Mulder is in next.

OUT! It's a procession for South Africa! Sri Lanka are returning the favour big time. Vishwa dishes out a length ball outside off, shaping away, de Kock prods forward, has a tame push inside the line and gets a fat outside edge behind. Kusal Mendis dives across to his left at second slip to take a brilliant catch. From 218/1, the hosts are now 5 down for 241. What a collapse!
On a length and wide outside off, it's left alone.
Almost drags it on! Fernando bowls a short and wide delivery outside off, de Kock tries to cut but ends up under edging it back towards the keeper.
This time Bavuma uses the angle of the bowler and works it in the gap at square leg for a run. That came more from the inside portion of his bat.
FOUR! Off the mark with a boundary. Vishwa switches to 'round the wicket and delivers another short ball outside off, Bavuma stands back and slaps it through cover-point.
Bangs in a short ball on off, de Kock pulls it in front of square leg for a run.
Temba Bavuma walks in next. South Africa lead by 78 runs. There is a bowling change as well. Vishwa Fernando returns.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Beauty of a delivery by Shanaka and he has removed the danger man cheaply. Lovely ball. It's on a length and close to off, du Plessis is caught inside the crease and has to play the trajectory. He tries to block with a straight blade but it nips away slightly to take the outside edge. Dickwella completes an easy catch and Sri Lanka are on a roll now.
Extra bounce from a length around off, du Plessis is taken aback as he defends it from the back foot.
Shortish and on off, de Kock moves across the stumps and turns it through square leg for a run.

EDGY FOUR! Very lucky for the South African skipper. Shanaka serves a delivery on a length around off and gets it to nip back into the batsman, de Kock gets forward to defend but it kisses the inside edge and runs past the stumps to the fine leg fence.
The batsman has just blocked that from his crease.
Shortish and on off, de Kock is on his back foot as he punches it square of the wicket on the off side. Not in the gap.
Length ball around off, Faf blocks this out on the front foot.
Length ball in the channel outside off, left alone.
Short bumper now on middle and leg, du Plessis ducks under it.
Length ball down the leg side, du Plessis lets it go.
Outside off, left alone.
FOUR! Nicely played! A length ball outside off, Faf plays it with soft hands and guides it down towards the third man boundary.
A length ball around off, du Plessis plays it with soft hands towards the gap at gully and third slip. They take three as the fielder chases the ball and returns it back.
In the channel outside off, left alone by du Plessis.
Short ball on middle, de Kock shuffles and rolls his wrists over to pul the ball towards deep square leg for a run.
Fuller ball around off, de Kock prods forward and defends this one towards mid-wicket.
Short of a length around middle, du Plessis tucks this towards fine leg and gets a single.
Fuller length ball outside off, de Kock looks to drive but the ball hits the inside part of the bat and goes in the gap at mid-wicket. They change ends.
Edgy! Another attempted cover drive but this one takes the outside edge and runs wide of backward point for a run.
A nice cover drive by the South African skipper but he picks out the fielder.

That's a snorter! Extra bounce from a length outside off, de Kock commits himself on the front foot as he looks to drive but it shoots up and strikes him on the gloves. Loops in the air but dies down quickly.
Very full, almost a yorker, de Kock digs it out to mid off.
Action replay of the previous delivery, it's been driven back to the bowler.
Fullish and on off, it's driven back to the bowler. Chameera jumps and parries it to the cover fielder.
Length ball around off, de Kock plays it softly on the on side and takes a run to get off the mark. Successful over this by Shanaka.
Length ball around off, de Kock gets on the front foot and defends it on the on side.

Good ball first up by Shanaka to de Kock. A fuller length around middle and leg, de Kock looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. Slight appeal from the bowler, but the ball was sliding down leg.
Skipper Quinton de Kock comes out to bat now.

DRS time! It's for a caught behind against Rassie van der Dussen. The umpire shakes his head but Sri Lanka are confident. Karunaratne takes the review and there is a spike on the Ultra Edge. The visitors have another breakthrough.

OUT! The onfield decision is overturned and Rassie van der Dussen trudges back. Shanaka comes up with a harmless delivery but hits the jackpot. A shortish ball sliding down the leg side, there to be smashed. Rassie tries to pull but fails to middle it. It goes past his gloves and Dickwella appeals after completing the catch. The umpire remains unmoved but Karunaratne agrees with his teammates and takes the DRS. The Ultra Edge shows some spike and that's the end for the local man. Two quick wickets for the Islanders and they have got a new lease of life here.
Fuller length around middle, Rassie prods forward and defends it on the on side.
Back of a length around middle, Rassie blocks this out on the off side.
Another delivery outside off has been left alone by du Plessis to complete a successful over for Chameera.
Back of a length ball close to off, Faf stands back and shoulders arms.
A length delivery is served in the zone outside off, some movement in the air, du Plessis leaves it alone.
Fuller length ball on off, it's defended back to the bowler. Solid.
Faf du Plessis arrives in the middle. He was in tremendous form at the SuperSport Park and would be eyeing another big score here. South Africa lead by 61 runs.

OUT! CAUGHT! The break does the trick for the Sri Lankans. A length ball outside off, Elgar gets on the front foot, trying to defend but ends up hanging his bat aimless outside off. It takes the outside edge and goes towards first slip where Thirimanne pouches it easily. A well-compiled knock by Elgar comes to an end but he will be disappointed as a big daddy hundred was there for the taking.
Length ball around middle, Elgar plays it with soft hands towards the gap at mid-wicket and collects a brace before the fielder returns the ball.

Drinks break. First hour has been safely negotiated by South Africa and they have swelled their lead to now 59 runs. The two set batsmen both got their personal milestones. Elgar continued his form from yesterday as he brought up his 13th Test century. Rassie who was more circumspect last night has looked fluent today on his way to his half-century. Sri Lankan bowlers have tried everything but apart from a half-chance at second slip, nothing has gone their way. Interesting play coming up after this break.
Slight inward movement from around middle, Rassie defends it towards short mid-wicket.
Pitches it up and lands it around off, van der Dussen is on the front foot this time in defense.
Good length delivery is just outside off, Rassie blocks it from the back foot. All too easy at the moment for the home team.
In the channel outside off, van der Dussen plays it down to gully.
This time the line is too straight and van der Dussen works it on the leg side, doesn't find the gap though.
Extra bounce hurries up the batsman. It's a touch short and outside off, van der Dussen is taken by surprise as it rises more than expectation but he somehow manages to keep it down towards gully.
FOUR! Beautiful drive! Chameera, you can't bowl this length to a set batsman like Elgar. An overpitched ball outside off, Elgar caresses this one through the covers.
Back of a length on middle, Elgar stands tall and defends this on the off side.
Shortish around middle and off, Elgar hops and blocks this out on the off side.
Short on middle, Rassie pulls it towards the left of the fielder at fine leg and takes a run. They thought for a second but decide against it.
Length ball outside off, inviting the drive but Rassie doesn't accept the invitation.
Fuller ball angling into the stumps, Elgar flicks this one towards deep square leg and changes ends.
Gets behind the line of the delivery and helps it to mid-wicket.
A rising delivery on middle, Rassie tries working it around the corner but takes a blow on his gloves as it rolls to the cover region.
Walks across the stumps and helps it towards square leg for a run.
FOUR! Easy pickings! Short delivery, it's banged on middle and leg, Elgar pulls it across the line and sends it to the fine leg fence.
A length ball is on and around off, Elgar blocks it back to the bowler.
Good length ball on middle and leg, van der Dussen nudges it behind square leg and rushes to the other end.
Shortish around middle, Elgar blocks this out on the pitch as his bottom hand comes off his bat.

FOUR BYES! A bumper now from Chameera on middle and leg. Elgar ducks under it and Dickwella behind the stumps jumps and tries to collect but it was way over him and the ball runs behind for a boundary.
Full again this time to Elgar, who pushes it back to the bowler.
Full ball around off, this time Rassie drives it to the left of the fielder at mid off and takes a quick run. 200 up for South Africa.
Length ball outside off, shapes away after pitching, Rassie lets it go through to the keeper.
Fuller ball around off, Rassie crouches and drives it nicely but straight to mid off.
On a good length in the zone outside off, Elgar has nothing to do with it.

FOUR! Superb shot! Another one played in the V! These two batsmen are batting riskfree. Too full in length around off, Elgar gets forward and drives it crisply down the ground for a glorious boundary.
Presses forward to a full ball and drives it back to the bowlelr.
The length is on the shorter side this time, outside off, Elgar protects his stumps and shoulders arms.
Once again the southpaw uses the angle of the bowler and works it on the leg side, this time straight to mid-wicket.
Dasun begins from 'round the wicket and angles in a length ball on off, Elgar turns it to the left of the mid-wicket fielder.
Another bowling change. Dasun Shanaka (6-1-13-0) comes into the attack as well.
Shortish on a length outside off, a bit of bounce too as it reaches the keeper, but Rassie leaves it alone.
Fuller ball on middle, Rassie pushes it down the ground towards mid on.
FOUR! Too straight this time from Chameera. Rassie just gets in the line of the ball and tucks this one fine towards the fine leg boundary. Rassie moves on to 64 now.
Fuller length on middle, Rassie punches this one too straight that it hits the stumps at the non-striker's end.
Fuller ball in the channel outside off, Rassie is not interested in playing that.
Length ball around off, Elgar pushes it towards backward point and calls his partner for a quick single.
FOUR! Gorgeous! Wow, Rassie! Asitha overpitches slightly around off, van der Dussen leans into the drive and caresses it through the gap between mid off and extra cover. The lead has raced to 33 now.

Almost drags it on! Asitha delivers in on a length close to off, Elgar tries to defend but it takes the inside edge, beats the stumps and runs away to fine leg for a run. That was an in-between length and the batsman was unsure whether to commit forward or go back.
Goes fuller and on middle, Elgar pushes it down towards mid on.
FOUR! That's the shot of a batsman in prime form. A slightly short in length delivery, outside off, Elgar smacks it through cover-point and fetches a boundary.
Good length ball on middle, Dean defends it back from the middle of the bat.

Appeal for an lbw! Not given again and this time Karunaratne is not taking the DRS. Once bitten, twice shy. A length delivery around leg, Elgar fails to defend and is hit on the pads. A little too high

DRS time! There is an appeal for lbw which is not entertained by the umpire. Dimuth Karunaratne decides to review it, out of desperation maybe. The replays roll in and the Lankan players also watch it on the screen. They immediately disperse, so you know what had happened... Yup, missing leg!

NOT OUT! A fullish ball on middle and leg, Rassie looks to flick but ends up missing his shot. Sri Lankan players appeal but nothing from the umpire. They take a review in desperation. The replays show the ball is missing the leg stump. Rassie survives and Sri Lanka lose a review.
Back of a length around middle, Rassie stands tall and flicks it straight to mid-wicket.
A length ball outside off, this time Rassie lets it go.
FOUR! Crunched. An overpitched ball outside off, Rassie bends down and absolutely crunches this one towards the cover boundary. Rassie looking in great touch today.
A fuller length ball down the leg side, Rassie looks to flick but misses.
Short and wide again by Fernando, Elgar plays it towards deep point for a single.
Good length ball on off, it's solidly blocked off the back foot. Both batsmen have now completed their respective milestones this morning.

FOUR! Delightful shot! Rassie van der Dussen brings up a fabulous half-century, a knock of grit and determination. His 4th Test fifty, second on his home ground. Too full in length on middle, Rassie unfurls a beautiful straight drive to get himself a boundary.
Fullish and on middle, Elgar presents a straight bat and pushes it down the ground. The mid off fielder makes a tumbling stop and they cross for a run.
Spears in a very full ball on middle, Elgar pushes it back in the direction of the bowler and his bottom hand once again comes off the handle.
Shortish this time, around off, Elgar is on his toes as he plays it down towards cover-point.
Full length ball on off, Elgar presses forward and defends it to the off side.
A length ball just outside off, Rassie is not interested in playing that.
Length ball around off, Rassie blocks this out.
Length ball outside off, Rassie looks to cut, but the ball keeps low and reaches the keeper at one bounce.
Fuller ball on middle, Elgar flicks this towards mid-wicket. The fielder there misfields and allows Elgar to change ends.

FOUR! CENTURY! What a way to get to his 13th Test century for Dean Elgar. He has batted brilliantly throughout his innings and gets to a well deserved century. A short and wide ball outside off, Elgar smashes this through the gap at covers to get to his ton in fine fashion.
Length ball around off stump, Elgar crouches and defends this one towards cover point.
Fernando delivers it on a length close to off, Rassie is forward as he pushes it to cover-point.
On a length and outside off, van der Dussen allows it through to the keeper.
Pitches it up and around off, this time Rassie unveils the off drive but finds mid off.
Good length ball outside off, it's left alone.

FOUR LEG BYES! A length ball on middle and leg, angling down, van der Dussen tries to flick but misses. It clips his pads and runs behind to the fence at fine leg. The Lankans were appealing but nothing doing as far as the umpire is concerned. No DRS taken, would have missed the leg stump.

DROPPED AND FOUR! Kusal Mendis fails to hang on. Asitha serves a fuller length ball on off, shaping away a bit, Rassie tries to play straight but it flies off the outside edge towards second slip where Kusal stretches his right hand out but it brushes his fingers and goes behind for a boundary at third man. Lucky escape for the local man.
Short and outside off, Elgar pokes that one towards point and stays on 98.
Fuller ball around middle, Elgar looks to flick but gets an outside edge which drops down towards covers. Nervous 90s playing in his mind here.
Nervy moment! A full toss on middle, Elgar tries to flick but gets a leading edge. It goes on one bounce to the point fielder.
Length ball this time outside off, Elgar lets it go.

FOUR! Smacked! This time he plays the cut to perfection. A shortish ball outside off, Elgar smashes it through the cover-point region for a boundary. Gets to 98 and South Africa are into the lead now.
Cut and a miss! A wide delivery outside off, Elgar looks to cut that without any foot movement but doesn't connect. A close shave this for Elgar in the 90s.
Yet another delivery in the channel outside off, Rassie shoulders arms to close the second over of the morning.
On a length and outside off, it's left alone with ease by van der Dussen.

Making the batsman play on this occasion. Asitha angles in a good length ball on off, van der Dussen defends it from the back foot. Umpire Erasmus walks forward and looks at the danger area. A friendly warning for the bowler.
Asitha hurls across a good length ball outside off, Rassie knows his off stump and makes a leave.

FOUR! A good positive start from Rassie van der Dussen. Short in length and close to off, Rassie stays back and pulls it handsomely over mid-wicket. A boundary to get going for South Africa's number 3.
Starts his spell with a shortish ball around off, Elgar stays back and takes his bottom hand off the handle as he taps it in front of square leg for a quick run. Moves to 94!
Asitha Fernando to operate from the other end. He was the pick of the bowlers on Day 1 and it's going to be a change of ends for him.
Fuller length angling across Rassie, who lets it go through to the keeper. Just 1 run from the first over of the day.
First runs of the morning for Elgar and the Proteas. A length ball around middle, Elgar pushes it towards mid on and calls his partner for a quick single.
A full ball now around off, Elgar digs it out towards the off side.
A good length outside off, Elgar lets it go.
A length ball in the channel outside off, Elgar shoulders arms to it.
Fernando starts with a fullish ball around off, Elgar pushes it towards cover.

That's all for the build-up! We are all set to get underway. Rassie van der Dussen and Dean Elgar are the overnight batsmen and they are amidst a century stand. It's going to be a very vital session for Sri Lanka. They are already behind in this Test and failing to make an impact in the first two hours will nearly throw them out of this game. How will they fare? Let's find out. Vishwa Fernando (10-0-40-0) to bowl first up and it will be Elgar on strike, 8 away from his century. Here we go...

Rassie van der Dussen comes up for a chat! He starts by saying that losing the toss, bowling first (South Africa also wanted to bat first), their bowlers really came out and showed some intent. It went perfectly according to the script, he adds. Shares that batting can get tricky at the Wanderers and you got to be very disciplined in playing straight and leaving well.
