Shares that he got a decent delivery in the last Test and has worked a bit on his technique. He is looking to shoulder the responsibility with the bat and he knows his ability and wants to be on the winning side. Smiles and tells that he doesn't want to read too much into the weather reports as there is a forecast for rain on the last two days.

Pitch report - JP Duminy is examining the playing area. He opines that the pitch will be great for batting on Day 2. Reckons the good length area around 4 to 5 metres away from the batsmen and outside their eye line should be the one that the Sri Lankan bowlers need to take into consideration. JP further adds that the Proteas need to be disciplined in leaving the ball which they did brilliantly last evening. Feels that the Sri Lankan bowlers must use this first hour and the cloudy conditions to take wickets early in the session.

Weather report - It's cloudy out there and things looking a bit dull, although there is no rain. The temperature is 21 degrees Celsius and the humidity is in the mid-60s. The conditions looking quite good if you are a fast bowler and Sri Lanka would be hoping that this is the divine intervention they need to make a comeback. Can their inexperienced pacers utilize the conditions? We will find out soon.

Hello and welcome everyone! Are you ready for another dose of Test cricket in the rainbow nation? Things are going very well for the home team after dominating the first day. Their bowlers took the initiative after Quinton de Kock lost the toss and did a very commendable job to bundle out Sri Lanka in a little over 40 overs. Right now, they are in total command with Dean Elgar and Rassie van der Dussen maximising the efforts of the Protea bowlers. The deficit is just 9 runs and they would be looking to make merry on possibly the best day for batting at the Wanderers. Stay tuned for more...

What to look for on Monday? Traffic jams, one supposes. People working on a normal Monday-Friday shift, who would have been enjoying a long weekend, will look to resume working. The last two words are what South Africa will look to do as well. Resume working. Take it hour by hour, session by session and bat well, grasping the opportunity to get back into form, before difficult series against Pakistan and Australia. Sri Lanka are behind the 8-ball but 4th January, 2021, could well see them possibly out of this Test match as well, if the Proteas bat the whole day. Can the visitors show some grit and fight and make the Proteas work for their runs? Adopt the policy which Wiaan Mulder stressed on Saturday. If not getting wickets, dry the runs and build the pressure. Join us from 10 am local (0800 GMT) for all the action from Day 2. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

When you get bundled out cheaply, you need to come out and show aggression. Try and force the issue on the opposition. Sri Lanka lacked that. Almost like a highlights package of the first Test, they leaked runs at 5 an over, showing how NOT to bowl with the new ball and wasting it. Then, they found some channel and stuck to it, getting Aiden Markram. But Elgar and van der Dussen blunted them out to frustration. So just the one wicket to show in 37 overs. Worryingly, not many outside edges taken, not many false shots induced and not many beat the bat.

The day could have gone either way. Dimuth Karunaratne won the toss, bravely chose to bat on a deck which had some grass on it. For an hour and a half, it seemed like it was a really good decision. Kusal Perera was going hammer and tongs. But then, the hammer broke and all hell broke loose. 72/1 it was at one stage and that catapulted to 110/7. Opportunity to stamp the authority gone. Thoughts flashing in mind - 'Why the decision to bat first?'

92. That is the number Dean Elgar will be going to bed with, thinking about a possible hundred he could have got. But other than that, a spectacular day for South Africa. A Rabada-less attack bundled out an injury-hit Sri Lanka in a shade over 40 overs and in response, have lost just a wicket and crept up very close to that 157 put up by the visitors. Perfect way to start the new year.

Oohhh.. nearly got him! Smart ball from Hasaranga. Slips in the slider, lands it on middle and leg, Elgar does what he has been doing all over - push to the leg side. So he tries to do a ctrl+C and a ctrl+V but then, the ball skids through and turns away. Now, Dean tries to do a ctrl+Z, looking to play a new stroke while adjusting, aiming to push to the off side but is squared up. Gets an outside edge but luckily for him, it is wide of slip, to his left! A single taken. STUMPS ON DAY 1, SOUTH AFRICA TRAIL BY 9!
Another ball, which sees the same thing. So control C plus control V for whatever has happened on the previous few balls.
The googly, around middle and off, blocked out in one of the ugliest manners possible.
Similar ball, this is pushed towards short mid-wicket.
Full and around middle, pushed back to the bowler.
Should be the last over of the day. Can Elgar channel a Gilchrist and go for the century?
Tossed up, around middle, pushed to the leg side.
Outside off, the outswinger, let through.
FOUR! A gift. Half volley, on the pads, van der Dussen flicks it through mid-wicket for a boundary. The stand moves to 113 and Rassie moves to 40.
Change in angle. Chameera is coming around the wicket now.
Fuller and wider outside off, let through.
On a good length, outside off, coming in, close to the off stump, but Rassie knows where his off stump is and lets it go. 69 balls left in the day, but only 3 minutes to go.
Outside off, shaping away, another leave by van der Dussen.
On a length, outside off, left alone.
Slightly short around off, Rassie plays it towards covers on the backfoot and sneaks a quick single.
Floated on off, Rassie lunges and blocks this out.
Flatter ball around middle and leg, Elgar tucks this on the on side and rotates the strike.
Floated ball around off, Elgar covers his stumps and defends this solidly.
Fuller this time on middle and leg, Elgar looks to tuck on the leg side but can't clear square leg.
Flatter around middle and off, Elgar pushes it towards cover.
On a length, outside off, let through to the keeper.
Fuller, outside off, let through to the keeper once again. 79 balls left in the day but only 10 minutes to go.
Back of a length outside off, the bat stays lifted.
Full and outside off, driven on the up, but straight to short exra cover.
Full and outside off, swinging away, left alone.
Dushmantha Chameera is back on. 5-0-26-0 so far.
IN THE AIR.. FOUR! Full and wide outside off, van der Dussen leans and then slices it over point. The ball lands over the fielder and then races to the fence. The deficit is now 16.
Floated ball on middle and leg, Rassie lenges forward and plays it down mid on and takes a quick single. Elgar will be off strike the next over courtesy this single by Rassie.
Tossed up outside off, inviting the drive, Rassie lets it go through to the keeper.
Flatter around middle, Rassie flicks this one towards mid-wicket.

FOUR! The short cover almost comes into play! Hasaranga overcorrects himself, bowling an overpitched ball outside off. Van der Dussen leans and drives this uppishly, but well over the man at short cover.
Straightaway, a change in field. Short leg comes out and a catcher goes toward short cover. There is sweeper cover as well.
FOUR! Beautiful cut shot. Slighly short ball outside off, Rassie rocks back and cuts it past backward point for a boundary.
Tossed up ball around middle and leg, Rassie defends it out on the off side.
Around middle and leg, nudged to the leg side.
Ahh.... careful, Dean! Full and wide outside off, DE drives away from his body and gets beaten!

Excellent. Simply excellent from Rassie van der Dussen. This is like the slog overs of a white-ball game where you need to give the strike back to the set batsman. Rassie of course, is well set, but he understands that there is not much time left for the day and Elgar is racing against time for his hundred. Nudges this towards mid-wicket, calls for a quick single and the batsmen cross even before Asitha himself can get to the ball.
Into the 90s now, is Dean. A length ball, down the leg side, just tucked around the corner, towards fine leg for a single.

FOUR! Wow. It's raining boundaries. Who thought Dean would be in a position to score a century tonight? Full and around middle, not overpitched by any means, but Elgar leans and just modifies his wrists, in a subtle manner, to get it to the left of mid on. The partnership is worth 92 now.
A short ball again, outside off, ducked under once more.
WIDE. Short ball, too high, outside off, Elgar let it be.
Flatter around middle and leg, Rassie defends this on the back foot. Expensive first over by Hasaranga.
Slightly short around middle, Elgar rocks back and tucks this towards deep mid-wicket and collects a run.
Floated ball on middle and leg, Elgar lunges forwards and defends.
FOUR! Second boundary of the over. Again an overpitched ball, this time on middle and leg, Elgar flicks it towards the deep square leg area to collect four more.
Floated ball around middle and leg, Elgar tucks this one towards fine leg and takes a couple.
FOUR! Not a good way to start by Hasaranga. An overpitched ball outside off, Elgar drives it past the cover fielder. The fielder from cover tries to chase the ball down but fails.

Finally. Spin. After normal Stumps time. Ideally, this should be the time we should be shutting our shop but because we have so many overs left, we have a half-an-hour overtime. Wanindu Hasaranga comes on. Pretty defensive field to start. 4 men on the boundary.
Around middle, solidly blocked out.
Short and outside off, this is cut away but there is insurance on this occasion. Deep point cuts it off to his left. A single taken.
FOUR! That has raced away. A length ball, outside off, Elgar punches this through covers and finds the boundary. The deficit is now 48. Elgar moves into the 70s with that.
A short ball, outside off, Elgar sways away from the line.
Outside off, punched toward point where it is stopped with a dive.
Full and outside off, angling away, played with an open bat face towards point.
Outside off, on a length, Rassie gets across and shoulders arms. 'THAT'S THE OVER', says Marais Erasmus.
A bit too straight, worked through square leg for a single. 109 balls left in the day, but just 34 minutes remaining (extended).

'AIYOOOOOOO!' goes Dickwella and this time it is waranteed. Vishwa dangles the carrot outside off and draws Dean into the drive. DE goes after it but his feet do not move. Resultingly, the inside edge is induced but it hits him on the pads. Fernando smiles, looking at Elgar.
FOUR! 'AAARGH!' cries Vishwa. Not a good ball at all. Short and wide outside off, Elgar lashes out the cut and gets it to the right of backward point. The stand is worth 70 now.
Full and outside off, Elgar crouches, then lifts his bat skywards, reminding us of Robin Smith from England and then lets it pass.
Landed outside off, angling away, left alone.
Outside off, on a fuller length, Rassie shoulders arms.
Full and outside off, swinging away, left alone.
A back of a length delivery, around off, tucked towards short mid-wicket.
Outside off, on a good length, shaping away, shouldered arms to.
Better ball, on a length, around off, nudged to the leg side.

FOUR! Oh dear. No, Asitha, no. Well, this is your first game, understandably but you cannot do this at international level, especially in the final session of the day. Gentle long hop, around middle and off, hardly any pace, just like a warm-up delivery, van der Dussen picks the length in a trice and pulls it through mid-wicket. 100 UP FOR SOUTH AFRICA. 57 behind. 119 balls left in the day, but just 40 minutes remaining (extended).
We have a bowling change. Asitha Fernando is back into action. 7-2-14-1 so far.
A short ball, outside off, DE looks to pull but is months early into the shot. The ball hits his left shoulder and rolls to the off side.
Full and down the leg side, flick shot missed.
Yes, this one comes back in but the line is that 4th and 5th stump outside off. Dean pushes it tentatively to the off side.
Better, landing on a length, outside off, rising a touch, left alone. Now, if he can stay on this line consistently.

FOUR BYES. More runs. A length ball, angled down the leg side, Elgar looks to tuck but misses. Dickwella tries to get across to his right but the ball shoots past, to the fine leg fence. The stand moves to 62 now.
FOUR! Wide, short, outside off, Elgar throws his bat at it and does well to control it, to get it behind point. It actually hit the toe end of the bat.
Outside off, on a length, moving away, left alone, inducing a 'AIYOOOOOOOOOOOO!' from Niroshan Dickwella.
A length ball, outside off, Rassie shoulders arms.
Again, on a length, outside off, Rassie pushes this to the on side.
Good length ball again, outside off, Rassie stays back and blocks it to the off side.
Good length area, now this is the one which seems to be having variable bounce. Stays low a touch and is well blocked out.
On a length, outside off, pushed toward the off side.
Outside off, stays low, DE adjusts well, to push it away, but still gets it off the inner half towards short mid-wicket.
WIDE. Short ball, banged into the deck, but way too high, outside off. Soars over.
Landed outside off, allowed to go through.

Down the leg side, Dean leans and works it through mid-wicket. Minod Bhanuka tracks it down to his right from deep square leg, dives and then pushes the ball into play. Two runs taken. Elgar moves to 60.
Full and outside off, swinging away, left alone.
On a length, outside off, van der Dussen punches it on the up through the covers. Kusal Mendis chases it down and stops it before the ropes. Three runs taken. 50-RUN STAND IS UP.
Full and around off, swinging in, driven back to the bowler.
FOUR! Edged away. Outside off, Elgar looks to play that with soft hands. The outside edge is induced but it runs past gully to the third man fence.
On a length, outside off, pushed back to the bowler.
A length ball, outside off, shaping into the batsman, pushed to the off side.
Full and outside off, pushed towards mid off.
A short ball, outside off, Elgar sways away and shoulders arms.
A length ball, outside off, pushed towards point.
Length bal on middle and off, Rassie blocks this out towards mid off.
Fuller, outside off, pushed towards cover.
A length ball, shaping away, pushed towards cover.
Around off, pushed in front of point for a single.
Short and outside off, left alone.
Nice timing by Rassie here. a fuller ball on the pads, Rassie flicks it towards the mid-wicket area. The fielder from mid on gives it a chase and stops it just before the ropes. Three taken.
Vishwa Fernando is back on. 6-0-21-0 so far.
Length ball outside off, left alone.
FOUR! FIFTY! That will do make him more confident. A fullish ball outside off, Elgar leans on the drive and places it towards the cover boundary to  bring up his 16th Fifty.
Beautiful ball. A good length ball outside off, shapes away after pitching. Elgar looks to play at but gets beaten by the movement.
Length ball around off, Elgar defends but the ball hits on the high part of the bat.
A short ball, outside off, Elgar looks to defend but the ball rises up suddenly. He manages to get his gloves out of the way.
Action straightaway after the break. A fuller length outside off, Elgar goes for the drive but doesn't connect. That just missed the outside edge.

Drinks! A good hour of cricket after the Tea break. Sri Lanka have bowled some tight lines and have looked to apply pressure but don't have more wickets to show for. The Proteas meanwhile are going nicely with Elgar holding guard and Rassie van der Dussen also biding his time at the crease. Interesting last hour and a bit coming up after this break.
Shortish around middle, Elgar tucks this one towards deep square leg for a single. That takes him to 49 now.
Length ball around off, Elgar blocks this out.
FOUR! Nicely punched. A fuller length ball on the stumps, Elgar just leans forward and punches this one down the ground for a boundary.
Short ball on middle, Rassie pulls this one nicely towards deep square leg but gets just a single.
Length ball around off, Rassie blocks this out towards the bowler.
Length ball outside off, Rassie lets it go.
Around off, on a length, blocked from the crease.
Around off, pushed towards cover.
Outside off, on a length, Dean looks to slash but misses.

Ask the Australians. Ask the English. Ask the Indians. This is a norm with Dean Elgar. He will get 10,000 inside edges, outside edges, have numerous plays and misses but will not throw his wicket away. Full and outside off, DE looks to drive but gets a thick inside edge which scoots past the leg stump towards fine leg. A couple of runs taken.
On a length, outside off, angling away, left alone.
Excellent stop. Full and around middle, Elgar flicks it through mid-wicket but the fielder there dives to his right and makes a terrific stop. Guess that was Vishwa Fernando.
Down the leg side, on a length, helped through fine leg for a run.
Tries that Nataraja shot again, with his right leg in the air and works it wide of mid on. Gets three runs for his efforts. Moves to 10. 169 balls left in the day, 82 minutes remaining (extended).
Full and outside off, moving away, let through.
Around off, pushed towards mid on.

FOUR! That is nicely played. A short ball, around middle, van der Dussen lifts his left leg, swivels a touch and pulls it all along the ground, through square leg, for a boundary. The trail is under a 100 now.
Full and outside off, Rassie gets a good stride forward and lets it go.
Outside off, Dean looks to punch it through the off side but the ball jars onto the bat, due to which, his bottom hand comes off. The ball goes off the toe end of the bat towards cover.
Another buffet ball. On middle, pushed towards mid on.
Full and outside off, Elgar lunges and pushes it towards point.
WIDE. A wild bouncer, around middle, Dean lets it pass.
Full and around middle, buffet ball, but not accepted by Elgar. His flick find short mid-wicket.
Outside off, on a length, pushed to the off side.
Full and outside off, Elgar reaches out, looks to drive but mistimes it to cover.
Outside off, a solid forward defense from Rassie.
Full and outside off, van der Dussen leans and drives it towards mid off.
Back of a length, outside off, Rassie arches back and lets it pass.
Outside off, left alone.
A short ball, pulled through mid-wicket for a couple.
A short ball, around off, Rassie ducks and lets it pass.
A length ball, tucked towards mid-wicket for a run.
A short ball, outside off, Rassie lets it through again.
Back of a length, outside off, pushed towards cover.
Pushed off the back foot on this occasion.
Around off, on a shortish length, blocked down the track.
Full and outside off, pushed through the covers for a single.
Length ball outside off, Rassie again leaves it alone.
Short and wide outside off, Rassie lets it go.
Shortish around off, Elgar pulls this one towards deep square leg for a single.
Length ball around middle and off, Elgar defends this out.
Length ball around off, Elgar blocks this on the off side.
Length ball around off, Elgar pushes it towards point.
Ends with a fuller ball outside off, Rassie drives it towards point.
A fuller length ball angling into the pads, Rassie misses the ball and gets hit on the pads. Huge appeal but no review taken. Might have missed the stumps.
Fuller ball outside off, driven nicely but straight to covers.
A length ball in the channel outside off, Rassie lets it go.
Length ball around off, played it towards covers for a single.
Fuller ball on the pads, Elgar misses his flick and gets hit on the pads.
Fuller length outside off, Rassie is not interested in playing that.
Length ball outside off, van der Dussen lets it go to the keeper.
Shortish on middle and leg, pulled away towards deep square leg for a single.
Length ball around off, Elgar pokes this towards point.

FOUR! EDGY! Very well bowled by Chameera. On a length, outside off, Elgar looks to defend but the ball rises suddenly and squares him up. The outside edge is taken and it flies behind gully. The ball races to the third man fence.
FOUR! Welcome to bowling crease, Mr. Chameera. Starts of with a shortish ball around off, Elgar pulls this towards mid-wicket for boundary.
Here's Dushmantha Chameera, who also can get it up in terms of pace.
Good over by Fernando. Length ball inviting the drive, Rassie doesn't accept the invitation.
Length ball around off, blocked solidly.
Length ball in the channel outside off, van der Dussen leaves it alone.
Similar ball around off, shapes away, RvdD lets it go.
Fuller ball in the channel outside off, Rassie lets it be.
Length ball on middle, van der Dussen looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Fuller ball outside off, shapes away after pitching, Elgar leaves it alone.
Shortish around off, Elgar plays it towards mid off.
Length ball around off, Elgar pushes this one towards the gap at mid-wicket and collects a brace before the fielder returns the ball.
Length ball on middle, Elgar blocks this out.
Fuller ball wide outside off, Elgar goes for the drive but doesn't connect.
Fuller ball outside off, Elgar leaves it alone.
Outside off, going away, let through.

Huge shout for LBW. Not given. Seemed to be going down the leg side. Also, the challenge for the seamers here at the Wanderers is the height. This is pitched on a good length and shapes back in too, but hits the inner part of Rassie's right thigh. Too high and going down too. But have to admire the plan from Asitha. Kept making the ball go away from van der Dussen and then got this one to come back.
Full and outside off, left alone again.
A length ball, outside off, swinging away, van der Dussen shoulders arms.
Nicely-judged single. On a length outside off, Elgar pushes it towards cover and takes a quick run.
Full and outside off, driven straight to mid off.
Outside off, Dean plays this with an angled bat, in front of point and a misfield alows him a single. Vishwa looks at the field and the fielders, wondering how on earth did a single get scored there.
A length ball, around middle, pushed towards mid on. 229 balls left in the day, 131 minutes remaining (extended).
Outside off, on a length, Elgar leans and punches, but finds backward point. There is a point and a gully in place as well. He scores a lot of runs through that area.
Full and outside off, coming in a touch, let through.
Full and outside off, Elgar walks into the shot and drives it back.
A length ball, outside off, left alone.
Outside off, Rassie looks to defend it with soft hands, but gets an outside edge to gully. A very good over from Asitha.
Outside off, back of a length, pushed towards point.
Landed outside off, fuller in length, left alone.
Local boy Rassie van der Dussen walks in at number 3, replacing Markram. Rassie plays all his provincial cricket here.

OUT! CAUGHT AT SLIP! Well, this is news. South Africa have lost an early wicket! Stop the press. Debutant Asitha Fernando has his maiden Test wicket. Loose, loose shot from Markram. The ball is pitched on a length, outside off, with a hint of away movement. Aiden is initially looking to play straight, then tries to adjust to the late movement and edges it. Straight into the hands of Kusal Mendis at second slip.
Shorter in length, around off, pushed away towards cover.
Full and outside off, pretty wide, swinging further away, left alone. 239 balls left in the day, 140 minutes to go (extended).
Around off, on a length, watchfully defended to the off side.

Huh? A short ball, around middle, DE looks to pull. But then looks to bail out. His bat hangs like a periscope in the air while the ball goes off the face of the bat, well wide of short mid-wicket. Two runs taken.
Outside off, on a length, pushed towards cover.
Full and outside off, Dean leans and presses it towards point.
Full and wide outside off, left alone.

FOUR! Just a touch. Almost like playing in front of a bowling machine. Full and outside off, Elgar gets across, watches the ball under his eyes, till the very last moment, then without moving his feet much,just pushes at the ball. That too, not a hard one, a soft one at that, so that, even if there is an edge, it will not carry. The ball hits the face of the bat and gains propulsion once it makes contact with the lush outfield.
Vishwa Fernando to continue from the other end. 3-0-12-0 so far.
Landed outside off, Aiden looks to repeat the shot which he played on the fourth ball of this over, punching it behind gully, but this time it is stopped. 6 runs in the first over post Tea.
A length ball, outside off, AM gets across and defends.
Outside off, on a length, Markram guides this with soft hands behind gully, for a couple. The deficit is now 129.

FOUR LEG BYES. A bit too greedy. Asitha looks to get the shape away from the right-hander, but he wants to do it from middle stump. What happens instead is the ball goes straight on. Markram misses his flick and the ball goes off his pads to the fine leg fence. 249 balls left in the day, 147 minutes remaining (extended).
Ahaa... nice. 140ks. Full and outside off, swinging away, Aiden does not get sucked into the drive.
On a length, outside off, Markram shoulders arms.

Welcome back. The players are back out in the middle. The odds are heavily stacked in favour of South Africa. Can Sri Lanka offer some fight? Here's Asitha Fernando to start off proceedings post Tea. 2-0-10-0 so far.
... DAY 1, FINAL SESSION ...

Too little data to look into the Sri Lankan attack but they are looking at a long session ahead. 42 overs left. If the Proteas maintain this current rate or score at a rate similar to the one in the first Test, plenty of runs are on offer and the visitors could be trailing by Stumps itself. Join us back at 3 pm local (1300 GMT) for the final session of play.

Perfect mini session for South Africa. No wickets lost and runs being scored at a fine rate. The opening batsmen might have been a bit nervous with just 20-odd minutes for Tea but they have ridden it well. Of course, the Lankan pair of Fernandos was nowhere close to the 145-plus mark of the Protean pace battery. Just the one-odd ball swung and beat the outside edge but otherwise, it was a fairly easy passage of play.
Length ball outside off, Elgar pushes it towards point. With that it's Tea on Day 1.
A length ball outside off, Elgar shoulders arms to it.
Length ball around off, Elgar keeps it away.
FOUR! Boundaries keep coming for the Proteas. A shortish ball around off, Elgar pulls this one to the left of the fine leg fielder for a boundary. 4000 TEST RUNS FOR DEAN ELGAR.
Length ball around off, Elgar bunts this down on the off side.
Fuller length around off, Elgar looks to play but withdraws and lets it go.
Fuller ball outside off, shapes away after pitching, Markram lets it go.
Back of a length around mddle, Elgar tucks this towards fine leg for a single.
FOUR! Second boundary of the over. Short ball around off, Elgar this time pulls it fine towards the square leg boundary.
Fuller this time around middle, Elgar looks to flick but gets an outside edge towards point.
FOUR! Short ball around off, Elgar rocks back and pulls this towards the square leg boundary.
Short of a length on middle. Elgar looks to tuck but gets hit in the pads.

Good running. A fuller ball around off, Elgar pushes it towards cover and takes a quick single. There is a bit of miscommunication between the batsmen but eventually they make it through. The fielder has a shy at the striker's end but misses. Markram was in though.
Length ball outside off, Elgar lets it go.
Shortish around middle, Markram pushes it with soft hands towards cover point and takes a run.
Fuller length, outside off, angling across, Markram leaves it alone.
A length ball around middle, Markram hops and blocks this out.
Fuller ball around off, Markram lunges forward and defends this one straight.
Fuller ball outside off, Elgar plays it towards cover. Good first over by Fernando.
Short of a length on middle, Markram tucks this one towards deep square leg for a single.
Fuller this time around off, Markram pushes it towards the gully fielder.
Good length around middle, Markram gets behind and defends that.
Fuller ball around off, shapes away after pitching, Markram leaves it alone.
Good length ball around off, Markram defends this out. Good start by Fernando.
Asitha Fernando, on debut, is given the new ball.
Short and outside off, left alone.
Outside off, pushed towards cover for a run.
On a good length, outside off, angling away, shouldered arms to.
Much better from Vishwa. Full and around middle, swinging in, Elgar looks to drive but gets it off the inner half of the bat towards fine leg. A single taken.
Outside off, on a length, left alone.
FOUR! What a lovely ball. IF YOU ARE A BATSMAN. Gentle half volley, on the pads, Elgar leans and flicks it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Back for the chase! Dean Elgar and Aiden Markram are the openers for South Africa. Vishwa Fernando to begin proceedings with the new ball. Three slips waiting.

So, only 67 to get for the home team. They would like to bat out the remaining period before Lunch watchfully and then go after the target in the afternoon. Can Sri Lanka pick a few early wickets to make South Africa nervous? Let's find out soon.

The first hour of Day 3 saw Sri Lankan captain getting to his 10th Test ton. He along with Dickwella scored at a rate of 6 in the first 4 overs. But just when Sri Lanka were looking good, Nortje got the better of Karunaratne and in the very next over, Dickwella was sent packing by Ngidi. The duo of Shanaka and Hasaranga looked solid for a brief period but Mulder with a knack of taking wickets got rid of the former in his very first over. Sipamla then came into the attack and wrapped the Sri Lankan innings by taking the remaining 3 wickets in a jiffy.

Fantastic bowling show by South Africa once again and now they need just 67 runs to clean sweep the Test series! They were a bit off-colour last evening but were right on the button this morning. The Islanders lost the plot and managed just 61 runs for the loss of 6 wickets. Lungi Ngidi has a big smile on his face, he missed out on his fifer but is happy for his team.

OUT! Off stump goes for a walk! Sipamla steams in and darts in a pacy length ball around off, it skids on after landing, beating the defensive bat of Asitha. It goes on to uproot the off stump and Sri Lanka are all out for 211!
Play and a miss! Fullish length wide outside off, Asitha throws his bat at it but fails to connect.
Asitha Fernando is the last batsman.
Big appeal for a caught behind! The finger stays down but there was some noise. Quinton de Kock is convinced and takes the DRS.

OUT! Number 9 goes down! Superb delivery. A touch short and juts outside off, Chameera feels for it inside the line with zero footwork and gets a faint outside edge behind. Quinton de Kock catches it and appeals but nothing from the umpire. The DRS is taken quickly and Ultra Edge finds a spike.
Good length ball on off, Chameera tries to defend it from the back foot but gets it away of the outside edge to point. Looks for a run but is sent back.
The batsman has just blocked that from his crease.
Beaten! Sipamla is in a really good rhythm. Serves a back of a length ball on off, nipping away, Chameera pushes and misses.
Good length delivery outside off, Fernando has tame push inside the line as he misses.
Sliding down the leg side, Vishwa tries flicking but misses.
A length ball on off, keeping low, Fernando defends it to the off side.
Huge shout for a caught behind! The finger has gone up. Vishwa has opted for the DRS immediately as Ngidi celebrates his fifth wicket. Hang on a second, there is no edge, Ultra Edge detects nothing.

NOT OUT! A peach of a ball from Ngidi. Length ball around off, shapes just a little away and goes through the defense of Fernando. There was a noise and the umpire had his finger up. Review taken straightaway. Replays show that the ball hit the back pocket and not his bat. However Ultra Edge detects nothing as the ball passes the bat. The umpire overturns his decision. Ngidi has to wait for his 5-fer here.
Length ball around off, jags back in and thuds into the pads of Fernando, who misses the flick shot.
Length ball around off, Fernando defends this one tentatively.
Too full in length on middle, it's worked through square leg and they cross for a run.
Vishwa Fernando is the new batsman.

OUT! Sound of timber! A peach of a delivery followed by a slightly fuller length ball around off, shaping in. Hasaranga possibly got rattled by the last delivery, tries to chance his arm and look for a big shot. Misses the ball completely and has his stumps destroyed. Sipamla is absolutely pumped, he had to wait for his chance and has managed to leave his impact straightaway. Sri Lanka lose their fourth wicket this morning and are effectively 64/8!
Oooohhhh... that missed the outside edge and the off stump by a whisker. This one pitches on a length close to off and straightens, Wanindu is squared up in defense and gets beaten all ends up.
FOUR! Streaky one! Fuller in length and outside off, Hasaranga attempts a loose drive at it and gets a thick outside edge wide of gully for a boundary.
Full length ball angling in from around off, Hasaranga defends it quite comfortably.
Bowling change. Lutho Sipamla (8-1-34-0) replaces Mulder from this end.
Around off, that is defended solidly off the front foot.
Ends the over with a fuller length ball around off. Chameera looks to drive but the ball sneaks through to the keeper.
A length ball around off, Chameera pushes this one towards point.
The plan is to bowl short here. A bumper on middle and leg, Chameera sits under it.
Length ball on leg stump, Hasaranga shuffles and clips this one towards fine leg for a run.
Short ball on middle and leg, Hasaranga ducks under it.
The batsman has just blocked that from his crease.
Keshav Maharaj is leaving the field. Maybe, he hurt his fingers while attempting for the catch or doing the backup of a throw in the previous over.
Just one ball to negotiate and Chameera does well by leaving a length ball outside off.

On a length and outside off, staying a touch low, Wanindu does well to ease it through point. They collect a couple as Ngidi was a bit lazy in attacking the ball. He eventually fires in a wild throw at the striker's end. Maharaj jumps to back up the throw but it brushes his fingers and goes behind. An overthrow is conceded. De Kock is seen shaking his head. Dushmantha has only one ball to survive.
Gets on the front foot to a length ball and pushes it to covers.
FOUR! A leg stump half-volley and Hasaranga cashes in. He leans forward and across before flicking it wide of Maharaj at mid-wicket for a boundary. 200 up for Sri Lanka.
Back of a length ball outside off, Hasaranga hangs back and steers it through point for a brace.

Dropped? Seems that it fell just short of Maharaj. Fuller length ball on middle and leg, Hasaranga flicks it across the line and it drops short of Keshav at mid-wicket. He does well to dive and stop it from racing away.
Another bumper on middle, Chameera ducks under it.
Short of a length on middle, Hasaranga tucks this towards deep square leg and takes a run. The initial call was for two but the fielder in the deep does well to keep it to a single.
Back of a length around middle, tucked towards square leg.
Bumper around  middle and leg, Shanaka ducks under it and lets it go.
Length ball on middle and leg, Hasaranag plays it back to the bowler.
FOUR BYES! A short ball down the leg side, Hasaranga ducks under it. The ball bounces over de Kock and runs to the boundary. Bonus runs for Sri Lanka, their lead is one short of touching 50.
Angles in a full length ball on off, staying a bit low, Chameera defends it from the back foot to the off side.
Dushmantha Chameera is the new batsman.

OUT! Mulder fools the batsman with a slower one. He dishes out a fuller length ball on middle at 123 kph, Shanaka is early into his shot as he attempts to whip it across the line. Ends up ballooning a simple catch to Sipamla at mid on. Another soft dismissal this morning for the visiting team. Sri Lanka are effectively 45/7!
Fuller length ball on off, angling in, Shanaka solidly blocks it to the off side.
Shortish and outside off, Dasun pushes it towards cover-point and eyes a run but is sent back.
The batsman has just watchfully blocked this out.
Good length ball on off, defended off the back foot by Shanaka.
Wiaan Mulder (11-2-43-0) to have a go now, replacing Ngidi from this end.
Back of a length on middle, Shanaka tucks this one towards fine leg for a single. Good batting this by Shanaka making Nortje bowl at the stumps.
Probing Shanaka outside off with a length ball, but Shanaka is not interested in playing that.
Length ball but too wide outside off, Shanaka watches it go to the keeper.
Length ball outside off, Shanaka is confident in his leave.
Slightly shortish outside off, Shanaka watches it closely and then sways away from it. He keeps his bat away from the ball.
Fuller length just outside off, Shanaka lets it go through to de Kock.
Probes with a fuller length ball on off, Wanindu stays back and offers a dead bat in defense. The search for a fifer continues for Ngidi!
On middle, angling in, Hasaranga gets back and defends it by closing the face of his bat. It rolls to short mid-wicket.
Angling into the batsman from outside off, on a length, Shanaka gets forward and pushes it with gentle hands to cover-point for a brisk run.
Good length delivery outside off, Shanaka plants his front foot forward and then makes a leave.
FOUR! Superb shot! Lovely wristwork shown by Shanaka. Too full and straight from Ngidi, Dasun rotates his wrists and flicks it supremely through mid-wicket for a boundary. The lead is now 43.
That is defended solidly off the front foot.
Back of a length on middle, defended back towards the bowler.
Ohh, That bounced from a length. A length ball outside off, shapes away after pitching. Hasaranga looks to cut but the ball bounces above the bat. A wry smile on Hasaranga's face.
Back of a length coming in with the angle, Shanaka tucks this one towards deep square leg for a run.
Length ball outside off, Shanaka comes forward and shoulders arms to it.
Hasaranga too is off the mark as he pushes a length ball around off towards cover-point for a single.
Shortish around off, Shanaka rocks back and tucks this one towards square leg to get off the mark.
Watchful! Fuller and close to off, this one is nipping back in, Hasaranga lands his front foot towards and defends it back. End of a probing over by Lungi.
A length ball around off, Hasaranga pushes it with an angled bat to covers.

Beaten comprehensively once again! Action replay of the last delivery. Moving away from the batsman off the seam, this time Wanindu tries to force the issue by opting for a big shot down the ground. Misses and the ball wasn't too far away from the outside edge.
Beaten all ends up! Beautiful bowling. Ngidi angles in a fuller length ball around off, Hasaranga tries to defend but it shapes away off the seam to beat the outside edge. Unplayable.
Uses the angle of the bowler and pushes a fuller length ball to mid on.
Good length ball on off, Hasaranga defends it back from the crease.
Almost gets his man. A length ball around off, shapes away after pitching. Shanaka looks to defend but the ball misses the outside edge by not much. Good over this by Nortje.
A bumper now around off, Shanaka sways away from it.
Nortje goes wide of the crease, bowls a length ball outside off, Shanaka is smart to leave that one.
Length outside off, Shanaka shoulders arms to it.
A length ball, but still wide outside off, for Shanaka to play at it. Left alone.
Fuller length ball in the channel outside off, Shanaka is not interested in playing that.
Targets the off stump with a fuller length ball, Hasaranga does well to block it from the crease. End of another successful over for the Proteas.
A slight bit of inward movement from outside off, Wanindu defends it close to his front pad.
A length ball on off, Hasaranga drives it off his front foot to covers.
Wanindu Hasaranga is in next. Two new batsmen at the crease now but both have shown good batting form in this Test series. Sri Lanka need them now the most.

OUT! One brings two and all of a sudden, Sri Lanka have lost both their overnight batsmen. Ngidi hurls across a fuller length ball around off, there is a slight away deviation as it hits the deck and Dickwella decides to heave it over the leg side. The ball nips away to take the leading half of his bat and flies in the air at covers. Bavuma sprints across to his right and takes the skier easily. Four wickets for Lungi and he has been South Africa's best bowler in the second innings. Sri Lanka are effectively 36/6!

FOUR! Nicely played by Dickwella. A back of a length delivery outside off, at 132 kph, Dickwella allows the ball to come to him and then just uses the bounce to steer it behind backward point. There was a man at the fence but it was played wide of him.
On a good length and wide outside off, an easy leave for Dickwella.
A bouncer on middle, Dickwella ducks and de Kock fails to collect. It goes behind and there is a long stop. They cross for a bye.
Dasun Shanaka is the new batsman.

OUT! CAUGHT! Nortje strikes. A back of a length ball into the body, Karunaratne tries to play the Nataraja pull shot but is hurried by the extra pace and gets a top edge that balloons towards square leg. Mulder takes one of the easiest catches there but after taking it blinks his eyes as if to tell, he nearly lost it in the sky. A fine innings by Karunaratne is over. South Africa are elated as they get the prized wicket of the Sri Lankan skipper. The lead is 31.
Length ball outside off, pushed towards covers.
Plenty of bounce on this pitch. A shortish length around off, hurries Karunaratne as he hops and tucks this to the left of square leg for a run.
Quick run. A length ball outside off, Dimuth looks to cut but the ball hits the outer part of the bat and goes towards point. Bavuma there has a shy at the non-striker's end but misses.
Back of a length around middle, Karunaratne hops and tucks this one towards square leg.
The length is slightly fuller than usual, outside off, Dickwella presses forward and pushes it towards wide mid off.
Good length delivery outside off, left alone by Niroshan.
Plenty of movement on this ball. A length delivery close to off, it nips away after hitting the deck and Niroshan leaves it alone.

Ohh that shoots up from a length. A shortish length ball around middle, Dimuth is hurried up as he hops and tucks this one towards square leg. His bottom hand came off the bat as he tried to play that ball.

FOUR! CENTURY! A captain's innings here from Dimuth Karunaratne. His 10th Test ton and he brings up in style. A shortish ball outside off, Karunaratne cuts that one through the cover-point region and gets to a well deserved hundred. FOUR! Excellent drive! A slightly overpitched ball around off, Karunaratne leans into the drive and plays it through the covers. On 97 now is Karunaratne.

FOUR! Shot! Ngidi thrives for movement and ends up bowling a juicy half-volley outside off. Dickwella plays a check-drive, finds good timing and placement to fetch a boundary at covers. The stand crosses fifty now, a very handy one!
Good leave. That's a tempter by Ngidi. On a length and close to off. It holds its line as well. Niroshan shoulders arms.
A length ball around off, shaping in, Dickwella defends it with an angled bat.
Pitches it full and keeps it close to off, Dickwella is half-forward as he defends it to the off side.
This time Ngidi angles in a fuller length ball on middle, Karunaratne flicks it through square leg for a run, moves to 93.
Starts with a shortish length ball outside off, Karunaratne shoulders arms and it travels to de Kock at a good height.
Lungi Ngidi (9-3-26-3) to speed in from the other end.

Back of a length on middle, Dickwella stands tall and defends it back towards the bowler. Nortje picks and tries to throw the ball at the stumps at the striker's end. Some aggression first up from Nortje.
Length ball around off, Dickwella leaves that alone.
FOUR! Nicely played. Shortish ball outside off, Dickwella punches it through the gap between third slip and gully and gets his first boundary of the morning.
First runs for Sri Lanka and Karunaratne. A shortish ball around off, tucked away towards fine leg for a single.
Shortish ball around off, Karunaratne hops and defends it towards square leg. The extra bounce on this delivery hurried up the Lankan skipper.
Nortje is on the money straightaway. A length ball around off, Dimuth pushes it towards point.

Time to get underway! The players are making their way out to the middle. Dimuth Karunaratne and Niroshan Dickwella are the overnight batsmen. Anrich Nortje to operate first up with three slips and a gully. Here we go...

Lahiru Thirimanne comes forward for a chat as well! Says that it was a great fightback by the bowlers especially. Adds that they have to back it up with the bat and a lead of 150-plus will be a great bonus. Hitting the right areas was the plan with the ball, shares Lahiru. On the pitch, Lahiru replies that in the first innings, after Lunch, there wasn't much movement and calls the wicket unpredictable.

Lungi Ngidi is up for a chat! The speedster calls their performance on Day 2 below-par but not much they can do about it now. Feels that the pitch has quickened up a touch. Shares that on Day 1 it was jagging around a bit but there is still some nip and swing on offer.  On his own performance, he calls it below-par as well and is a bit embarrassed to get two wickets by bowling down the leg side. Believes that a lead of 100 is something they will be comfortable chasing.

Pitch report - JP Duminy is near the surface and says that the pitch has a fine covering of grass and also has more consistency in terms of bounce until now. He reckons that Day 2 is generally considered as good for batting but the Sri Lankan bowlers bowled brilliantly led by Vishwa Fernando who swung the ball both ways. Also praises the young pacer for using different angles while bowling and talks about his releasing points from both over and around the wicket which confused the batsmen. JP feels that both teams will be very mindful of the threat that this pitch brings.
Weather report - It's partly cloudy and there are 40 percent chances of rain on Day 3. The maximum temperature is expected to be around 21 degrees Celsius while the humidity will be in the high-50s.

Usually, Day 3 is a moving day in a Test. But this Test has moved quickly right from the first day. Yesterday, Sri Lanka tried to make a comeback and fought brilliantly both with the bat and ball. After conceding a lead of 145 in the first innings, the Islanders managed to wipe off the deficit and now lead by 5 runs. Captain Karunaratne has looked solid and Dickwella offered him good company last evening. The South Africa bowlers took 4 wickets courtesy some fine bowling by Lungi Ngidi but they did lack consistency. The hosts would look to be on the money and make use of the early morning conditions. Should be a cracking first hour.

11 wickets on the first day and 13 wickets on Day 2 - It's been a Test match dominated by the bowlers! But strangely, on both the days, it's a batsman who shone towards the end - Dean Elgar spent a night in the 90s after the opening day and then Dimuth Karunaratne went to bed last night 9 away from his century. A very vital morning session awaits us. Stay with us for more...

Right then! On Day 3, Sri Lanka would hope that they can build on their lead and set the hosts a sizable score to chase while South Africa, on the other hand, need to pick up the remaining wickets as quickly as possible. They still hold the cards at the moment and would hope that they can do better with the ball on Day 3. Day 3 will begin on Tuesday, 5th January 2021 at 1000 local (0800 GMT). Join us for that. Till then, cheers and take care.

In reply, Sri Lanka did not get off to a good start as they lost Kusal Perera for just one. But then, Dimuth Karunaratne and Lahiru Thirimanne built a brilliant stand and brought the visitors back in the game. Thirimanne fell against the run of play and that started a mini-collapse as they lost two more quick wickets. Since then, the Sri Lankan skipper and Niroshan Dickwella have managed to survive till Stumps. Karunaratne has looked superb and will hope that he can continue on Day 3. Dickwella has looked fidgety but has managed to survive. The bowling from South Africa was led by Lungi Ngidi as he has already picked up three wickets but needs support from the other end. They have been a little unlucky with the edges not going to hand. Overall, it was a hard-fought day.

Sri Lanka started the day behind the 8-ball as Rassie van der Dussen and Dean Elgar continued their onslaught. Van der Dussen reached his fifty while Dean Elgar made his Ton and continued on his merry way but just before Lunch, the hosts lost both and then started the collapse. From 218 for 1, they slipped to 302 all out and that gave the Sri Lankans an opening. Nobody apart from Dean Elgar and Rassie van der Dussen could come to terms with the pitch. The Sri Lankan bowling was superb as Vishwa Fernando brought up his first 5-fer in Tests and he was well supported by Asitha Fernando and the others as well.

A day which has belonged to Sri Lanka but it is still South Africa who are on top. It has been a superb fightback from Sri Lanka though. They were down and out at the start of the day but the way their bowlers brought them back was just brilliant. There is quite a bit of work to be done for both teams when they take the field on Day 3.

In reply, trailing by a massive 145 runs, Sri Lanka were given an early blow by Lungi Ngidi who destroyed Kusal Perera's stumps. The South African bowlers bowled superbly with the new ball and kept the Lankan batsmen on the back foot. Thirimanne and Karunaratne though survived the rest of the period, they have a huge task in front of them. The third session will begin at 1500 local (1300 GMT). Do join us then.

Yet another good session for Sri Lanka but in the context of this Test match, they are still way behind. Their bowlers did a commendable job post the Lunch break to pick the remaining wickets, although the last wicket partnership between Ngidi and Sipamla frustrated them a bit. Vishwa Fernando has to be the star of the afternoon as the young man finished with his maiden Test fifer.

OUT! BOWLED! Ngidi strikes early and Perera can't repeat his 1st innings heroics. A length ball around off, nips back in sharply and goes between the bat and pad of Perera to hit the top of middle and leg. South Africa strike early and it's a massive blow for Sri Lanka. Lahiru Thirimanne has joined his skipper in the middle.
Play and a miss! Length ball outside off, Perera looks to smash that but ends up missing it altogether.
Angling away from the batsman, on a length, Karunaratne taps it down towards point and Perera looks for a run. He is sent back as Bavuma attacks the ball.
A single on this occasion. The line from Nortje is straight again and Perera tucks it away towards square leg for a run.

Nortje serves a back of a length ball on off, hitting the deck hard as usual, Kusal covers the line and blocks it safely.
Physio comes out. Magic spray is being applied on the fingers of Kusal Perera.
Extra bounce hurries the batsman! On a good length around leg, Perera tries to work it on the leg side but the ball jumps and strikes him on the gloves. That would have hurt.
A good length ball on middle and off, Perera defends it back from the middle of the bat.
Anrich Nortje to share the new ball from the other end. He is fresh from a 6-wicket haul and would love to add more to his tally.
Length ball outside off, Dimuth lets it go through to the keeper. Maiden to start from Ngidi.

Length around middle, Karunaratne defends it towards mid-wicket.

That's your lot for the day. It was a ruthless show by South Africa to win the Test series and now they will prepare for the challenge in Pakistan. For Sri Lanka, it was a tour to forget and they will return home to host England. We look forward to your company for future games. Until then, it's goodbye and cheers!

South African skipper, Quinton de Kock doesn't think it was a revenge series for them and mentions that after a year like 2020, they just wanted to get off to a good start in their next season. Tells that he is quite impressed with a lot of performances and adds that the seniors also fulfilled their roles. Mentions that Keshav Maharaj was a bit unlucky but he understands his role. Confirms that there is no major injury concern with Maharaj. Praises his four seamers and feels that they will get better with more experience. Shares that it's mixed emotions travelling to Pakistan as he is keen to play some cricket but the bubble life can be frustrating.

Sri Lankan skipper, Dimuth Karunaratne starts by saying that they had a good start with the bat but then suddenly lost a few quick wickets. Feels that they fought back hard but only in patches. Counts the positives and names Kusal Perera who performed well and also praises Asitha Fernando and Vishwa Fernando. Hopes to take the positives into the England series. Shares that Mathews might come back, Chandimal is also recovering and that's good news for them. Feels that they can dominate at home and they have a couple of spinners to trouble England.

DEAN ELGAR GETS THE MAN OF THE MATCH AND SERIES AWARD! Says that he was frustrated after getting out in the 90s in the first Test but he just wanted to keep that aside. Adds that he had some success in these conditions and it's great to contribute. Regarding his improved scoring rate, Elgar jokes that they are now calling him the Kusal Perera of South Africa. Mentions that he is not taking a lot of unnecessary risks and this is something that has come with experience. States that he just looks to score and stay positive. On the upcoming tour of Pakistan, Elgar shares that he has never been there and it's going to be an awesome challenge, something that every cricketer has to experience. Talks about his partnership with Markram and tells that they have worked really hard and opening the batting for the same team in domestic cricket has helped. Feels there is good chemistry between them and they help each other in getting better.

There were big hopes from the pair of Dimuth Karunaratne and Niroshan Dickwella but they encountered a motivated South African bowling attack. Lungi Ngidi and Anrich Nortje bowled a hostile spell and then it was the same old story with the Lankan batting. Lutho Sipamla finished things off and Sri Lanka managed to set a target of only 67 which was easily overhauled by the home team.

The evening of Day 2 was all about the Sri Lankan fightback with Dimuth Karunaratne and Lahiru Thirimanne leading the charge. They added 85 for the second wicket and things started to return to normalcy for the visitors. However, a mini-collapse in the evening pushed them back slightly. They entered Day 3 ahead by 5 runs and with the hope to build a big lead.

Getting bundled out for only 157 in a little over 40 overs on Day 1, as a team, you are always behind the 8-ball. That was the case with Sri Lanka as well. Dean Elgar and Rassie van der Dussen compounded their misery with a record partnership for the second wicket at this venue. Through Vishwa Fernando's magnificent 5-wicket haul, the touring team did make a little comeback but a deficit of 145 on this pitch was always going to haunt them.

The Islanders were decimated in Centurion and the script didn't change much in Johannesburg. Depleted by injuries, they fielded a second choice XI and it was a brave decision by Dimuth Karunaratne to bat first on a spicy Wanderers pitch. Soon that call was proved to be wrong as Anrich Nortje ran amok and destroyed their batting with a 6-wicket haul. Not to forget Wiaan Mulder's contributions too as his first spell showed the African bowlers the path after an unconvincing beginning.
Commanding victory for South Africa and they win their first Test series since 2018. By doing so, they have also avenged their last Test series loss against Sri Lanka. Job well done by the Proteas!

Just a little over 30 minutes taken by South Africa to score the remaining runs. The South African balcony is ecstatic and the players are now getting together to congratulate each other. Mark Boucher will be a very satisfied coach and Quinton de Kock is also happy as he starts his Test captaincy stint with a series win.

That's the winning run! Floated around middle and leg, Elgar tucks this one towards deep mid-wicket and takes a single to celebrate with his hands up. South Africa win by 10 wickets and take the series 2-0!
Floated around middle and leg, Elgar pushes this one softly towards long on and takes a couple of runs. Scores level with that two runs.
A back foot defense to complete a maiden over. 3 needed more.
Gets behind the line of the fuller length ball and pushes it back to the bowler.
On and around off, defended from the crease to covers.
Outside off, left alone.

Flatter and on middle, helped in the gap at mid-wicket for a run.
Floated around off, Markram plays that one towards cover for no run.

Hurls across a good length delivery outside off, shaping away, Aiden shoulders arms.
Angles in a length ball on middle and leg, Markram works it through mid-wicket for a couple of runs. Under 10 needed now.
Short in length and outside off, Elgar forces it off the back foot to deep cover for one.
Excellent delivery! Angling into the batsman on a length and nipping away, Elgar pushes at it and misses.

Length ball around off, punched towards point for another run.
Another two. This time a length ball around off, Markram plays it through the cover-point area and comes back for the second.

Whoa! This is a shot Elgar never plays. Attempts to muscle his drive through the cover region but he misses the ball badly. With no pressure, Dean is trying something out of his comfort zone.

Pitches it up and around off, Elgar mistimes his drive off the inner half to mid on.

Gets behind the line of the delivery and pushes it to mid off.

Stays on the back foot and uses the angle of the bowler to work it in the gap at mid-wicket. A couple is taken.
Shortish and on off, it's punched off the back foot to point where the fielder fumbles slightly but no run taken.

Pops up in the air... DROPS SAFELY! Vishwa runs in from 'round the wicket and digs in a short ball on middle. Markram jumps to fend it off and it takes the shoulder of his bat. It lobs in the air but dies down near the surface. No short leg there otherwise he would have been in business.
Vishwa Fernando to continue from the other end.
Dean Elgar is not ready and pulls out. Asitha aborts his run midway and returns to his mark.
Nice bumper to finish the over. A short ball around middle and leg, Elgar ducks and then tries to pull but it misses his bat through to the keeper.
Length ball around off, Elgar pushes this one towards extra cover.

Length ball around off,  Markram pushes this towards point and takes a quick single.
Shortish on middle, Elgar pulls this one towards deep square leg for a single.
FOUR! What a dessert to get after Lunch. A short and wide ball outside off, Elgar punches this one off the back foot through the covers.

Welcome back for what could be the final session of this Test series. Funny things have happened in cricket but the chances of anything other than a South African win here looks next to impossible. Only 43 runs left for a win and Sri Lanka would like to avoid a 10-wicket loss. Let's see how things pan out.
.....DAY 3, SECOND SESSION.....

A satisfying session for South Africa! Their bowlers did an incredible job to bundle out Sri Lanka this morning and restricted their lead to only 66. The African openers had a little period of 5 overs to negotiate before Lunch and they did that safely by scoring 24 runs. Another 43 needed for a clean sweep and we will be back to finish the formality at 12.40 pm local (1040 GMT).
Back of a length ball on off, Aiden Markram punches it off his back foot to cover-point. That will be LUNCH ON DAY 3!
A length ball on middle and leg, nudged through mid-wicket for a couple of runs.

Is that taken? Kusal Mendis is claiming the catch. Umpire Erasmus is unsure and walks up to his partner. They have a chat and decide to go upstairs. Sri Lanka are very sure about it and almost leaving the ground for Lunch. Soft signal is out. Let's find out. It has touched the ground, the soft signal is overturned and the Lankan players return to bowl the remaining balls of the over.

NOT OUT! A close one this. A fuller length ball outside off, Markram looks to drive but gets an outside edge towards the slip cordon. Mendis from second slip dives across to his left and claims the catch. Markram stands his ground and the umpires send it upstairs by giving the soft signal as out. Replays show the ball has touched the ground as Mendis caught it. There is enough conclusive evidence to overturn the soft signal and the third umpire flashes NOT OUT on the big screen. Markram survives.
No run.
Back of a length around off, Markram pushes this one towards point.
Length ball around middle, Markram stands tall and defends it back to the bowler.
Works a full ball to the right of mid-wicket and collects a single.  45 needed more!
Loopy and full on off, Markram presses forward in defense.
Tossed up ball on off, a googly, defended by Markram.
Misfield and FOUR! Very full in length outside off, Markram drills his drive to the left of mid off. Shanaka moves there, slides but it goes through his legs for a boundary.
Too full in length on middle, Elgar flicks it through mid-wicket for a single.
Full and floated on middle, knocked wide of mid on for a run.

Nicely punched off the back foot. A back of a length ball around off, Markram rocks back and punches this one through the covers and collects a brace.
Back of a length ball around off, Markram hops and keeps this one out.
Length ball around off, Elgar pushes it towards point and calls his partner for a quick single.

Movement back into the batsman with extra bounce, Markram keeps it out with one hand.
